<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, France Help Increase Russia's Role in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Germany and France vowed to help
Russia play a bigger role in European affairs as leaders of the
three countries concluded their first informal meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to do everything to prevent the appearance of the
impression that someone is trying to isolate Russia after the Cold
War," said German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Kohl added the summit with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
French President Jacques Chirac was not directed against the
U.S. or any other European country.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac said that France wanted to increase Russia's
role in Europe. "We realize the importance of confiding, close
relations between the EU and Russia, which are close poles of the
multipolar world of tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
The three leaders, who will meet again in France in May 1999,
also discussed a joint project to develop a European transport
plane for the 21st century based on the Russian-Ukrainian An-70
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
They also plan to create a special rescue service to tackle
natural and industrial disasters in the three countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
