<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Envoy on Zimbabwe's Land Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Out-going British High Commissioner
to Zimbabwe, Martin Williams Thursday said Britain and Zimbabwe must
find amicable ways to resolve differences over the land redistribution
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Williams was speaking at a farewell luncheon hosted for him in
Harare, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said although the two countries have had differences in the
land redistribution issue, these must be settled amicably in the
interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
''My government is prepared to put some money to help the
Zimbabwean government in their current programs, for instance in the
land redistribution exercise and we wish if that standstill is solved
amicably,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Zimbabwean government, which has already designated
1,500 farms for compulsory acquisition, would only compensate
affected farmers for improvements on their properties and not for the
value of the soil.
</P>
<P>
The British government criticized the policy of the Zimbabwean
government and sticked to the policy of willing-sale and willing-buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
