<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Be Affected by New European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- European bankers have
predicted that South Africa's trade and financial transactions
with Europe are likely to be affected when the Euro, a single
currency is introduced in the continent early next year.
</P>
<P>
Local daily, Sowetan quoted Tom Boardman, managing director of
Europe-based BOE Investment Bank, as reporing Thursday that the
launch of the Euro will be a major world event. He urged South
African businesses to prepare themselves ahead of the event.
</P>
<P>
The Euro is expected to be introduced in January when 11
European currencies amalgamate.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the Euro has been largely ignored in
South Africa as some nebulous future events... People are now
realizing that it is less than a year away and they had better
find out how it will affect them," Boardman said.
</P>
<P>
Pat McArdle, a senior official of Ulster Bank Group said there
were obvious practical implications for South African financial
institutions business in the sphere of international trade.
</P>
<P>
Since European cross-border price differences will become
obvious, a single currency will make it easier for South African
trade to span a wide area of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The major opportunity for South African companies will be to
make it easier to resource imports because greater price
transparency will boost competition," said McArdle.
</P>
<P>
He said since Britain and Germany have traditionally been
South Africa's two largest trading partners, local companies will
now find that they can source their imports at more favorable
prices in one of other 10 Euro-denomination countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission Wednesday recommended 11 European
Union countries for single currency, the Euro. They are Germany,
France, Italy, Ireland, Spain, Belgium, Finland, Portugal,
Austria, Luxembourg and Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
McArdle suggested that the Euro is likely to become
increasingly pervasive and may challenge the United States dollar
for world hegemony in the long term.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
