<HEADLINE> U.S. Grants $14.5m to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Hilarry Clinton, the U.S. first
lady, announced a grant of 14.5 million U.S. Dollars to Uganda
Wednesday, the New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a gathering in Makerere University in Kampala,
the first lady said 10 million is for non-government
organizations working to improve food security and responses to
conflict in the Great Lakes region, two million is for training
local women council executives in Uganda, two million is for a
new three-year northern Uganda initiative to rebuild
infrastructure, 500,000 is for non-government organizations
helping children abducted by the rebels of the Lord's Resistance
Army (LRA) in the north.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group acting in the north and has its bases and
training centers in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Hillary told her audience that the U.S. will put its pressure
on Sudan to stop its support for the LRA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Uganda Vice-President Specioza Wandera Kazibwe, Uganda first
lady Janet Museveni, Speaker of Parliament James Eapakhabulo,
cabinet ministers, university lecturers joined 6,000 students to
welcome the U.S. president on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Makerere University is the most famous university in the
country. it had trained famous political leaders and scientists
such as Jiulius Kambarage Nyerere, the former Tanzanian
president, and Daniel Arap Moi, the present president of Kenya.
</P>
</TEXT>
