<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Nigerian Youths Engaged in Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Federal Office of
Statistics (FOS) reported that only three percent of Nigerians
below 25 years old are engaged in agriculture in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a newly-issued publication titled "National Agricultural
Sample Census 1993/94", FOS said that the number of farmers aged
between 25 and 44 stands at 46 percent, while those aged between
45 and 59 account for 33 percent of the farming population.
</P>
<P>
FOS said earlier that an average of 61 percent of households
in the country are engaged in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a population of around 100 million.
</P>
<P>
As for the farmers' marital status, only four percent of them
are not married, whereas 84 percent are married and 12 percent
are widowed, divorced or separated, it said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that 59 percent of the farmers in Nigeria
have primary education, as against 28 percent with secondary
education and nine percent with post secondary education. The
number of those who never went to school stands at four percent.
</P>
<P>
The document reveals that 90 percent of Nigerians take
agriculture as primary occupation, two percent practise farming
as secondary occupation, while eight percent were primarily
engaged in agriculture but had other sideline occupations.
</P>
<P>
According to FOS, only 37 percent of the farmers in Nigeria
use chemical fertilizers in their farms, mostly in the north.
</P>
<P>
It said that 19 percent of them get their fertilizers from
government sources, six percent from cooperative societies and 60
percent from the open market.
</P>
<P>
Among those who do not use fertilizers, 52 percent blamed it
on high cost, while 23 percent did not know any source for
procuring the chemical substances.
</P>
<P>
FOS said that Nigerian farmers generally do not use pesticides
except Katsina State in the north.  
</P>
</TEXT>
