<HEADLINE> Kenya, U.S. Agree to Enhance Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
and U.S. President Bill Clinton have agreed that the existing
"good relations" between Kenya and the U.S. should be further
strengthened and deepened, the Kenya News Agency (KNA) reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The KNA report said that President Moi, who was in Uganda for
a regional summit, held a discussion with the U.S. president on
bilateral relations on Wednesday evening in Entebbe, Uganda.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Moi said that Kenya should be turned into
a peaceful, stable and prosperous country in which all
communities can develop together.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the on-going constitutional reform debate in the
East African country, he noted that all communities in Kenya
would be given a chance to present their views in the forthcoming
constitutional reform process, said the report.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, who is on a six-nation African tour, said
that he understood the situation in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In Moi's view, the meeting between Clinton and African leaders
at the regional summit marks "a new chapter in relations between
the U.S. and Africa".
</P>
<P>
After the summit, President Moi left Uganda for home on Wednesday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
