<HEADLINE> UK Female Prison Population at Highest Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- There is a significant increase in
the female population of prisons in England and Wales, with the
total number now standing at 3,053, the highest level since 1905,
according to figures published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper said that many prison officials share
the view that some female prisoners should not be in prison as it
is quite clear that a number of women in prison are there as a
direct result of poverty and abuse.
</P>
<P>
David Roddan, general secretary of the Prison Governors'
Association, was quoted as saying that "prison governors have been
aware for some years that imprisonment is being over-used".
</P>
<P>
He added that "This impacts particularly on women, because the
growth in the female prison population has been double that of the
male population over the past three years, and there has been no
corresponding increase in the number of the offenses being
committed by women".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that according to last year's report from the
Chief Inspector of Prisons, 70 percent of female prisoners posed
no security risk and should not be held in closed prisons.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the prison service called on the government to
examine the possibility of more community based outlets rather
than keeping female prisoners all in prison.
</P>
<P>
A Home Office spokesman was quoted as saying that the
government was trying to improve the public's perception of
community, non-custodial sentences and was carrying out trials on
electronic tagging and the use of curfews.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
