<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Faces Shortage of Education Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Education Minister
Gabriel Machinga said on Thursday that one of the most serious
problems facing the country's education is critical
shortage of teaching materials.
</P>
<P>
Machinga said this at a ceremony to mark the fifth anniversary
of the Herbert Chitepo Trust and the official opening of the
trust's new office in Harare, reported the Zimbabwe News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that it is impossible to improve the quality
of education when books are not available to both teachers and
students.
</P>
<P>
"The practice of sharing textbooks not only inconveniences the
pupils and the teachers, but also leads to the early destruction
of the few books available," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Without books it is impossible to stimulate reading and
writing among the new literates."
</P>
<P>
Machinga noted that the devalued purchasing power of the
Zimbabwean Dollar and the devastating effects of inflation in the
economy has greatly weakened the ability of parents to purchase
books for their children.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Herbert Chitepo Trust, launched in 1993 by
President Robert Mugabe,is an important vehicle in commemorating
and recognizing the outstanding work and achievements of the late
nationalist leader Herbert Chitepo in the fields of law and
politics.
</P>
<P>
The minister described late Chitepo as an outstanding
Zimbabwean scholar, a man of letters, a very committed educator
and an advocate for an independent, confident and resourceful
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
