<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Corporate Profits Drop Sharply in 4th Quarter 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. corporation profits
recorded the sharpest decline in nearly four years during the
fourth quarter of 1997 despite a robust economic growth as a
whole, the Commerce Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After-tax corporate profits slipped 2.3 percent in the fourth
quarter, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 483.7 billion
U.S. dollars, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The report, also includes a revision of previous estimates of
the gross domestic product, contained the department's first look
at profits in the fourth quarter. The drop was the worst since the
first quarter of 1994 and also the first since the July-October
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the revised figure, the U.S. quarterly GDP grew at
a brisk 3.7 percent annual pace. Though not quite as strong as the
3.9 percent estimated a month ago, that still is considered
robust.
</P>
<P>
However, for the year as a whole, the increase in after-tax
corporate profits, up 7.3 percent to 480.3 billion dollars,
outpaced the 3.8 percent increase in the economy's total output of
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter decline may extend the trends to this year.
Confronted with shortages of qualified workers, a result of the
lowest unemployment rate in 24 years, many employers have been
forced to raise wages. But, on the other hand, in many industries,
they haven't been able to raise the prices of their products in
fear of losing competition to much less expensive Asian
commodities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More UK Women Take to Smoking, Drinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The proportion of UK women who smoke
and drink heavily has started to rise recently after more than 20
years of steady decline as traditionally male patterns of life are
increasingly adopted by women, according to official figures
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 General Household Survey, published Thursday by the
Office for National Statistics, revealed that the proportion of
women smoking rose between 1994 and 1996 from 26 to 28 percent,
about to overtake the 29 percent of men who smoke.
</P>
<P>
The trend is most pronounced among young women, as 34 percent of
women aged 25-34 were smokers in 1996 compared with 30 percent two
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
The annual snapshot of contemporary British life also found that
women who drink heavily, particularly young professional women, are
also on the increase and are rapidly catching up with the drinking
levels of their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the number of women exceeding the
recommended drinking level has grown from 10 to 14 percent, but the
number for men has remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
This is again particularly pronounced among young women, as one
in four women aged 18-24 drank more than recommended in 1996
compared with one in seven in 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
