<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Parties Welcome Setting Deadline for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Parties involved in Northern Irish
peace talks on Thursday welcomed a decision to set the target for
the peace talks and vowed to do their best to reach an agreement
by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the talks, former U.S. senator George Mitchell,
decided on Wednesday to set April 9 as the deadline for a deal to
end the decades-long conflict in Northern Ireland. He also said
discussions would soon go into permanent session until a deal was
struck.
</P>
<P>
The feuding parties in the talks welcomed the decision, giving
new hope for a political settlement to the conflict in Britain's
divided province.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very significant development. It presents all
parties with the opportunity to reach an historic agreement," said
John Hume, leader of the Roman Catholic nationalist Social
Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
David Kerr, spokesman for the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), the
largest pro-British party in the province, said the UUP "will do
everything we can within reason to expedite an agreement from
these talks."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political arm of Irish Republican Army
guerrillas who oppose rule from Britain, saw it as an opportunity
to end centuries of conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Sinn Fein believes an agreement is possible within the
timeframe envisaged provided that all parties engage in good
faith," spokeswoman Bairbre de Brun said.
</P>
<P>
The British and Irish governments plan to hold referendums in
both Northern Ireland and the Irish republic in late May to decide
the fate of Northern Ireland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
