<HEADLINE> Cohen Warns Russia of Arms Sales to Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen on Thursday warned against any Russian arms sale to
Yugoslavia although Moscow has denied any such a sale as reported
in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions during a photo opportunity with
Finland Defense Minister Anneli Taina at Pentagon, Cohen said any
sale of Russian military weapons to Yugoslavia would violate the
Dayton peace agreement and threaten peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"This would be contrary to agreements, contrary to Dayton, and
we hope that the reports are not accurate... further sales and
transfers of weapons to the region would be counter-productive,"
Cohen told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We are hoping that we can encourage both parties to act
responsibly and we do not see a transfer of weapons being in the
interest of promoting peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, The New York Times reported that Russia had
agreed in principle to sell tanks, warplanes and other arms to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry denied
the report on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
