<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Sentence on Nurse Reaffirmed in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Thursday ruled
to keep in place a death sentence on a young nurse charged with
killing a patient and attempting to kill 29 others by injecting
lethal doses into them, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Alexandria Criminal Court reaffirmed the sentence on Aida
Nourreddine, which was ordered on March 11, after the approval of
the Mufti, Egypt's chief Muslim official, during the day.
</P>
<P>
Nourreddine, 25, working in the Alexandria University Hospital,
was arrested last August after 33 patients died due to respiratory
failure shortly after successful surgeries.
</P>
<P>
She was suspected of injecting into the patients a respiratory
muscle relaxant which choked them to death.
</P>
<P>
But she was charged with killing one patient as autopsy could
be conducted only on one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
But, meanwhile, she was also accused of attempting to murder 29
others who survived.
</P>
<P>
The nurse, however, pleaded innocent and accused doctors of
negligence and prescribing wrong medication for the patients.
</P>
<P>
Nourreddine's supporters are trying to make an appeal at the
Cessation Court, which is to make the final jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
During the investigation of her case, the nurse fell from the
third floor of the Prosecution Building of Alexandria, broke
several bones, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But it is not known whether she jumped out herself or was
pushed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police found that the dossiers of the victims
have disappeared, according to the Al-Ahram, one of Egypt's
national newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Hospital officials claimed that they have been disposed of, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the standard practice, the files should be kept
for five years, the Egyptian Gazette said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
