<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disarmament Conference to Establish Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament (CD)
adopted a compromise proposal by consensus here Thursday to
establish an ad hoc committee on negative security assurances and
appoint special coordinators for other issues on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Consultations on the composition of the ad hoc committee and
the special coordinators will be held between now and the
resumption of the second part of the 1998 session on May 11. The
first part opened on January 19 and will end on March 27.
</P>
<P>
However, the proposal did not enjoy complete support from the
CD members. Canada and South Africa said they did not back the
decision, but indicated they would not oppose it so as not to
block consensus.
</P>
<P>
Other countries backed the decision with reservations. The
representative of China called the decision "not strictly
satisfactory", adding that China had joined the consensus to show
as much as possible a flexible and constructive spirit.
</P>
<P>
Japan considered the decision not entirely satisfactory.
Nonetheless, its representative said that he was aware of the
necessity to begin work at the conference as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of India, Pakistan and Syria said the
proposal did not reflect their national positions, especially
regarding the priority they felt should be given to nuclear
disarmament. The representative of Egypt also stressed that
nuclear disarmament should receive priority attention, but said
the decision at least allowed the conference to begin concrete
work.
</P>
<P>
As for agenda item 1 entitled "Cessation of the nuclear arms
race and nuclear disarmament", the conference decided that it
would be the subject of further consultations under the authority
of the CD president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
