<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Willing to Work With S. Africa: Says Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Thursday that his country is willing to work with South
Africa through a "genuine partnership."
</P>
<P>
"As a new South Africa emerges, we seek a genuine partnership
based on mutual respect and mutual reward," Clinton told a joint
sitting of South African parliament in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"Simply put, America wants a strong South Africa, America
needs a strong South Africa. And we are determined to work with
you as you build a strong South Africa."
</P>
<P>
In the short speech broadcast live on South African national
television, Clinton also pledged to strengthen cooperation with
South Africa in dealing with international issues, such as the
fight against international crimes and the building of a
nuclear-free Africa.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the United States would shift its Africa
policy from aid to trade.
</P>
<P>
Questions like "What can we do for Africa, or whatever can we
do about Africa?" were wrong, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The right question should be: What can we do with Africa?"
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has worked out a U.S.-Africa Growth and
Opportunity Bill, which seeks to open African markets, replace
aid with trade, and grant better U.S. market access for African
exports.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa has expressed reservations about the
legislation, which has been approved by the U.S. House of
Representatives and now is going to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said Clinton's
formula -- trade, not aid -- was wrong. Africa, including South
Africa, needs both.
</P>
<P>
He said it was necessary to recognize that the U.S. and poor
African countries like Burkina Faso were not partners of equal
weight which could enter into an equal bargaining posture.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of South African Parliament's Trade and Industry
Committee, Rob Davies, said on Wednesday that the U.S. bill was a
rather "one-way determination and it is just straight direct
conditionalities."
</P>
<P>
To be eligible, African countries would have to meet a long
list of conditions, based on which the U.S. president would
decide whether a country did not engage in gross human rights
violations and was making progress towards establishing a
market-based economy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in his speech that his country will cooperate
with Africa as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Africa needs the world, but the world needs Africa, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0025 </DOCNO>
