<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Reiterates Position on Deployment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Thursday reiterated that
it can cancel the missile deal with Russia if President Glafcos
Clerides' proposal for demilitarization of the island is accepted
by the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Chirstos Stylianides made the remark at
his daily press briefing while commenting on recent statements by
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos that Greece will support
Cyprus in the event of a Turkish offensive against the island or
its defensive missile system expected to be deployed later this
year.
</P>
<P>
"The government is ready to look into the possibility of
suspending or canceling the deployment of the Russian missiles if
significant steps are made leading to the demilitarization of
Cyprus within a specified timetable," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered Russian-made surface-to-air
missiles system in January 1997. The deal was criticized by the
U.S. and some European Union (EU) member states, and Turkey has
threatened to strike the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides welcomed Pangalos' expression of support, saying
that his statement is part of the coordination between Greece and
Cyprus in defense and strategic matters, as these are defined in a
joint defense pact agreed between the two governments in November
1993.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the latest development on Cyprus problem,
Stylianides said the Cypriot government believes that further
pressure should be exerted to bow Turkish intransigence and "we
are trying to promote these views with the help of the Greek
government."
</P>
<P>
The government, he pointed out, wishes to see more effective
pressure by the international community, which would lead to a
comprehensive settlement, and hopes this can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The international peace efforts for a solution to the
protracted Cyprus problem have gone into deadlock since the
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash refused to attend further
peace negotiations unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus
is internationally recognized.
</P>
<P>
Denktash also insisted that the negotiations can be only
resumed on the basis of "state-to-state" talks, a precondition
rejected by the internationally recognized Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third of
the island following a short-lived pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Denktash declared unilaterally a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Voices Opposition to EU Farm Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government voiced strong
opposition early Thursday to the proposed European Union (EU)
agriculture reform plans, according to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Irish Agriculture Minister Joe Walsh Thursday told visiting EU
Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler that EU proposals to
reform the 15-nation bloc's agriculture policy were simply
unacceptable to his country.
</P>
<P>
Walsh said, "No government, no minister for agriculture could
accept these proposals in their present form and still claim to
represent the best interests of the Irish people."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the EU plans, which are designed to cut
Ireland's EU agriculture subsidies, were "seriously
disadvantageous to Irish agriculture and, by extension, to the
Irish economy".
</P>
<P>
The Dublin government is expected to put forward its argument
to the EU Commission and the EU Agenda 2000 council during the
negotiation period for at least a year, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fischler insisted that planned EU agriculture
reforms were necessary and realistic, but indicated that there was
still room for negotiation by saying the draft proposals were "not
carved in stone".
</P>
<P>
"There is room for manoeuvre here -- if Ireland sets out its
objections we can talk about them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform plans of the EU's Common Agricultural Policy,
due to come into force in 2000, there would be sharp reduction in
the level of guaranteed EU support prices for Irish cereals, beef
and milk in the form of direct aid.  
</P>
</TEXT>
