<HEADLINE> First Batch of Iraqi Pilgrims Leave for Saudi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of about 1,100
Iraqi pilgrims left here Thursday for Mecca, Saudi Arabia, to
perform Islam's holy pilgrimage, the hajj, the Iraqi News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
A farewell ceremony for the pilgrims was organized on the
occasion and attended by Iraqi Minister of Endowments and
Religious Affairs Abdul-Munim Ahmed Saleh and other officials.
</P>
<P>
The hajj is one of Islam's main tenets, requiring the
able-bodied Muslims to make a pilgrimage to Mecca, the birthplace
of Prophet Mohammed, in one's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had requested the U.N. sanctions committee to release 44
million U.S. dollars to cover Iraqi pilgrims expenses. The request
was approved on condition that the Iraqi government issued
travelers checks to the pilgrims to enable them to use the
Jordanian means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
The money would be deducted from the U.N.-administered Iraqi
frozen account and be transferred through Jordanian banks.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq rejected the proposal, demanding on grounds of
sovereignty that the money be deposited in the Iraqi central bank.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Iraq sent the first passenger aircraft to Jedda ever
since 1990, transporting 104 sick and aged Iraqi pilgrims to Saudi
Arabia without obtaining the approval of the U.N. Sanctions
Committee. It also sent helicopters to the borders with Saudi
Arabia to carry the pilgrims back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
