<HEADLINE> Russian President on Russian-French-German Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
believed that the Russian-French-German Summit held in Bor resort
near Moscow marks the beginning of the formation of a real
multipolar world, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said this at a press conference after his meeting with
French President Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
He said, "It is from here that a multipolar world will evolve, not
from any one state, but from a number of states, a number of
leaders."
</P>
<P>
"It is here that a multipolar approach is being formed, and it
is from here that it will spread around the world," he said,
adding there should be no discrimination against any state in the
modern world.
</P>
<P>
An expanded Europe will become a major force in today's
multipolar world, Yeltsin noted.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, Yeltsin, Chirac and Kohl also discussed work
on a European Security Charter.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made it clear that France opposed admission of the three
Baltic countries into NATO, according to Russian presidential
spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders also discussed Iraq problem, the situation in
Armenia's run-up to the presidential elections and the Iran
problem, as well as relations between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Kohl arrived in Moscow on Wednesday for the first
one-day informal summit with Yeltsin and left for home Thursday
evening.  
</P>
</TEXT>
