<HEADLINE> Franco-African Meeting Transparent, Fruitful: Ethiopian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin said Thursday the just-ended Franco-African foreign
minister meeting held in Ougadougou, Burkina Faso was transparent
and fruitful.
</P>
<P>
In a statement here after attending the meeting in Burkina
Faso, Seyoum said the meeting at which more than 30 African
countries took part, dealt at length on the security and crisis
in Africa, the Lome Convention, the implementation of the
decisions of the 1996 Burkina Faso summit and preparations for
the summit due to be held in France in November, this year.
</P>
<P>
On conflicts in Africa, Seyoum said, the meeting underlined
the need to consolidate the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
mechanism for conflict prevention, management and resolution and
urged the support of partners to this end.
</P>
<P>
He said, the meeting emphasized that sub-regional
organizations like the Inter-Governmental Authority on
Development (IGAD) and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) also need assistance in building their capacity
to fully exploit their understanding about conflicts and crisis
in Africa in the effort to bring about sustainable peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has also mentioned the importance of the
cooperation on the part of the United Nations Security Council
with regional and sub-regional organizations in the effort to
address the crisis in Africa, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum said both France and the African states have accepted
the necessity to revise the Lome Convention signed between the
Africa, Caribbean and Pacific countries and the European Union to
make it compatible to the existing international trade and
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that the meeting which deliberated on good-governance
in Africa has underlined the interdependence of good governance,
human rights and economic prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
