<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Expects Clinton's Visit to Result in More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The 14 member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have expressed the
hope that the current visit by United States President Bill
Clinton will result in more investment to African countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived in Cape Town, the legislative capital of South
Africa Thursday morning, on the fourth leg of his 12-day visit to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
SADC executive secretary Kaire Mbuende said what the region
did not want was for the visit to be seen as nothing more than
opportunities for the U.S. to pledge development aid to Southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"What we are hoping for is a serious dialogue on a number of
issues," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's share of U.S. direct foreign investment was two
percent. There was no justification at all for such a low figure,
given the continent's population and resources.
</P>
<P>
"The only way we can be taken seriously is when we discuss as
equals and not as a giver and a taker," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
After the showmanship of the visit, the SADC wanted to make
sure it had been taken seriously and send clear signals to the
U.S. that southern Africa was ready to do business.
</P>
<P>
"Our businessmen want to do business and there is potential
here for American investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of a U.S.-SADC memorandum of understanding
on trade and cooperation in 1996 in Gaborone, little had
happened, Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed by the then U.S. secretary for
commerce the late Ron Brown and Mbuende.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his arrival in South Africa, Clinton had visited
Ghana, Uganda and Rwanda. He is also scheduled to tour Botswana
and Senegal. 
</P>
