<HEADLINE> UNICEF Welcomes New Drug Treatment to HIV-AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said on Thursday that a new and strikingly
cost-effective drug treatment against mother-to-children
transmission of HIV during pregnancy will help fuel a major
expansion of the war against AIDS in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Carol Bellamy, UNICEF's Executive Director, said the
effectiveness of the new drug regime, together with estimates
of its cost effectiveness, would enable UNICEF and its partners
in the UN System to step up their response to prevent HIV/AIDS
in children.
</P>
<P>
"These recent developments are a breakthrough -- providing
new options for greatly reducing HIV transmission in pregnancy
and childbirth," Bellamy said. "But they also highlight the job
that remains to be done to reduce transmission to women in the
first place, and transmission through breastfeeding."
</P>
<P>
The new treatment involves using the antiretroviral drug AZT.
The procedure, found effective in field trials in Thailand, is
significantly cheaper than current treatments, does not require
intravenous administration, and can be used by women late in
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
"One thousand infants are born with HIV every day, most
of them in developing countries," Bellamy noted. " The new AZT
will make it possible to reduce that total dramatically."  
</P>
</TEXT>
