<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Plans to Step Up Drive to Prevent HIV-AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) is supporting efforts proven to be
successful to reduce mother-to-child transmission of HIV through
the use of antiretroviral drugs in Thailand, Carol Bellamy, UNICEF's
Executive Director, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
And efforts will be made over the next three months in a number
of UNICEF-assisted countries with a high prevalence of HIV,
Bellamy said, adding these countries include Botswana, Cote
D'Ivoire, Rwanda, Zambia, Cambodia and Viet Nam.
</P>
<P>
The way to accelerate program efforts includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Improve access to voluntary and confidential HIV counseling
and testing. UNICEF will continue to expand its efforts in this
area, working closely with governments, partner agencies and
non-governmental organizations to ensure that women, particularly
pregnant women, are given the means to know their HIV status.
</P>
<P>
-- Measures to strengthen and expand national and
community responses to HIV-AIDS, particularly in the areas of
awareness and prevention, legal reforms, family care and support,
both emotional and medical, for women who test positive for HIV as
well as measures with careful control targeting and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
-- Infant formula, at affordable prices and in the quantity
needed for about 6 months, for tested women with HIV who make an
informed choice in favor of this alternative. Formula with no
brand labels will be distributed at reduced cost through
existing community-based institutions with careful control,
targeting and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
-- Counseling and other assistance to ensure that families
are aware that formula can be fed by cup rather than feeding
bottles, which introduce additional costs and risks.
</P>
<P>
-- Ensured access to sufficient quantities of clean water,
fuel, soap, clean utensils, and community-level follow up to
ensure the formula is mixed as safely as possible and is fed in
adequate quantities for normal growth and development.
</P>
<P>
-- Partnership with local institutions and health workers,
building on existing UNICEF programs, to improve these
families' access to appropriate milks and foods for their
children beyond 6 months and their capacity to ensure good
feeding practices.
</P>
<P>
-- A monitoring system to assess the impact of the program
services on the survival and development of the children of women
living with HIV, as well as on breastfeeding practices among other
women in the same community.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
