wounded in an Israeli shelling of a village in south Lebanon on
Thursday, Lebanon's Voice of People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The two civilians were slightly wounded when Israeli troops
bombed the village of Balera Shiit, which borders the Israeli
self-styled security zone set up in 1985 to buffer guerrilla
attacks on its northern areas.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which damaged several homes in the village, came in
retaliation for Hezbollah fighters' raid earlier on an Israeli
post in the zone, according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group Hezbollah, or Party of God, is spearheading
a campaign to oust Israeli troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Lebanon would file a complaint over the
bombardment to a five-nation monitoring committee comprising
Lebanon, Israel, Syria, France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The committee has the job to supervise the execution of a 1996
ceasefire which bans firing from or at civilian targets on both
sides of the Lebanese-Israeli border. 
</P>
