<HEADLINE> France Responds to Clinton's Statement in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- France Thursday responded to the
statement made by U.S. President Bill Clinton in Rwanda, pointing
out that France asked for a reinforcement of U.N. peacekeeping
force in Rwanda when the genocide was taking place in the Spring
of 1994, but no one supported it.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in Kigali, capital of Rwanda, on Wednesday that
both the international community and the United States bear a
heavy responsibility for failing to intervene in Rwanda during the
genocide, in which 500,000 to 800,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus
were killed by the country's Hutu military.
</P>
<P>
"France, after the tragic events on April 6 of 1994 in Rwanda,
launched a heavy diplomatic campaign at the United Nations asking
it not to withdraw the MINUAR intervention force which was already
in Rwanda at that moment," said French Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
France asked U.N. to enlarge the peacekeeping force up to 5,500
soldiers, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
"Such a reinforced operation by the United Nations as was
called for by France at that time was not supported by anybody.
Nobody answered the pleading by France at that time," she said.
</P>
<P>
France has created a parliament mission of information on the
role France played in Rwanda from 1990 to 1994, after Paris was
accused of supporting the Hutus by some independent investigators
both at home and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
