property which should be preserved at any price," said d'Estaing
in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
RPR President Philippe Seguin said Wednesday that his party
could present itself alone in future elections, instead of as a
twin party with the UDF, after the UDF was plunged into a deep
crisis following the regional elections on March 15.
</P>
<P>
Five UDF politicians allied with the far-right National Front
(FN) in election of presidents of regional councils, while a UDF
politician has announced a plan to set up a new party to replace
the UDF.
</P>
<P>
D'Estaing was reelected the regional council president of
Auvergne while representing the UDF.
</P>
<P>
He expressed disagreement with the president of the
UDF-affiliated Democratic Force party, Francois Bayrou, who
announced a plan Wednesday to establish a new party to replace the
UDF.
</P>
<P>
"The solution of the problems of France will not come from the
parties.... If the UDF reorganizes itself and changes its name, it
will have neither advantage nor inconvenience," said d'Estaing.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Charles Millon, the former defense minister who
was re-elected to the presidency of the regional council of
Rhone-Alpes with the votes from the FN, should resign from his
post, d'Estaing said that it is up to Millon himself to decide.
</P>
