<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects U.S. Proposal on Military Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Greece Thursday expressed its
opposition to the U.S. proposal for a moratorium on military
flights over Cyprus, saying that Athens did not regard such a
proposal as a substantial step towards the demilitarization of the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that in contrast, Athens and Nicosia believed
that the installation of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles
would be "a substantial step towards demilitarization in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the missiles would not be installed
as scheduled unless steps were taken towards the full
demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
To bolster its defenses, Cyprus signed earlier last year a
contract with Russia to purchase and install the S-300 missiles,
but this did lead to opposition from northern Cyprus, Turkey and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to do everything possible to prevent
Nicosia from installing the missiles or launch a military strike
against the anti-aircraft systems. 
</P>
