<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Feted by Mandela as Differences Swept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Policy differences between
the U.S. and South Africa were temporarily swept aside on
Thursday afternoon as President Nelson Mandela laid on a full red
carpet treatment for President Bill Clinton in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
In a short and low-key address to a joint sitting of
parliament after a full ceremonial welcome by Mandela, Clinton
said Americans are now awakening to the promise and potential of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived in Cape Town Thursday morning for a
four-day state visit, played down differences between the U.S.
and South Africa, saying that like all partners they could not
agree on everything.
</P>
<P>
"Some times our interests and our views diverge, but that is
true even in family partnerships," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not give in to demands from those, including the
South African Communist Party, who hoped for an apology for
successive U.S. government's roles in aiding the former apartheid
regime.
</P>
<P>
White House Press Secretary Mike Mccurry later told reporters
that "President Clinton has pitched his remarks into the future,
he elected not to dwell on the U.S. government's policy in the
past."
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Clinton had put his words into practice
when he showed off his building skills at a self-help housing
project in the Cape Town city.
</P>
<P>
He said the project could prove a model for the rest of Africa
and the world, and promised an extra three million U.S. Dollars
in aid for it and similar projects in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
A courtesy call later by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki at
Clinton's hotel saw South Africa's future leader responding to a
newspaper report that he had attacked Clinton's flagship Africa
Growth and Opportunity Bill.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on an interview with a French magazine,
quoted Mbeki as saying that Clinton's bill is wrong.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also met leaders of opposition political parties after
his address in parliament, in what was described as informal
talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. leader is due to hold bilateral talks with Mandela on
Friday and several contentious issues are expected to be
discussed, including South Africa's controversial medicines
control legislation, which the U.S. drug industry believes
violates their patent rights.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will also reportedly try to persuade Mandela to bring
South Africa into an international anti-corruption initiative.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to invest Clinton with South Africa's
highest award, the Order of Good Hope, at Friday's state banquet.
</P>
<P>
On how Clinton would feel accepting the award -- he will share
it with his arch foe Libyan leader Muammar Gadaffi and others --
Mccurry said it had been given to a range of individuals and "the
President will accept that in the spirit in which it is given."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
