<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Incomes Maintain Strong Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. national personal
income rose 0.6 percent in February for the second consecutive
month, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 7.14
trillion U.S. dollars, exceeded the healthy 0.4 percent increase
in spending, to a seasonally adjusted rate of 5.66 trillion
dollars, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Spending rose 0.7 percent in January, revised up from a
previous estimate of 0.4 percent, the highest rise in last six
months.
</P>
<P>
Strong income gains in recent months reflect continued demand
for labor and an unemployment rate that dipped to a 24-year low of
4.6 percent in February. Personal spending has been stimulated by
low interest rates, a result of the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, some experts believe that by the second half of the
year, the Asian economic crisis will cause slower employment
growth, and thus slower income growth.
</P>
<P>
Most categories of income increased in February, including the
most important wages and salaries, up 0.9 percent after a 0.8
percent gain in January. Also higher were business owners' income,
transfer payments such as welfare and Social Security and interest
and dividend income. Farmers' income, however, declined for the
second consecutive month. Rental income also fell.
</P>
<P>
Disposable personal income or income after taxes, rose 0.6
percent, following a 0.8 percent gain the month before.
</P>
<P>
Because after-tax income grew faster than spending, Americans'
savings rate crept up from 4.2 percent in January to 4.3 percent
in February, also the highest in eight months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
