awaits in the House. The vote on the 18 billion U.S. dollars
measure to help deal with the Asian financial crisis was 84-16. In
a maneuver by Appropriations Chairman Stevens, it was attacked to
an emergency spending bill, ensuring IMF funding is on the table
when it is reconciled with a House version. House leaders have
held up IMF funds seeking leverage in areas such as abortion.
</P>
<P>
-- U.N. weapons inspectors searched one of Saddam Husssein's
palaces for eight hours in a test of Iraqi compliance with the deal
brokered recently by the U.N. secretary general. Diplomats from 20
nations accompanied the inspection team. A German envoy later said
no area was put off-limits. 
