<HEADLINE> Japan to Give Manila Loan for Economic Adjustment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan will provide a new economic
adjustment support loan of two billion yen (about 16 million U.S.
dollars) for the Philippines to continue its economic
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
An accord on the assistance was signed here Friday by
Philippines Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon and Japanese
Ambassador to Manila Hiroyuki Yushita.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Philippine Foreign Department said the grant
is intended to enhance the Philippines' efforts to sustain its
economic momentum through further structural adjustments in the
domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
The grant is part of Japan's "Emergency Measures to Stabilize
the Southeast Asian Economies" announced February this year in
Tokyo by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, they said.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the Philippines' second largest trading partner and
foreign investor, and the biggest provider of Official Development
Assistance.
</P>
<P>
Japan had provided a total of 7.4 billion U.S. dollars in
official development assistance to the Philippines from 1985 to
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
