<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Beats Chinese Taipei in Hong Kong Rugby International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Seven-time Cup winner and
defending champiom Fiji made a flying start by trouncing
lowly-fancied Chinese Taipei 61-0 on the opening day of the Credit
Suisse First Boston Hong Kong Rugby Sevens '98 tournament here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hottest for the title of the 510,000 U.S. dollars tournament as
the World Cup holder from last year's meet here, Fiji scored four
tries and as many conversions to lead the first half 28-0. It
added 33 more points in the second half to seal the triumph.
</P>
<P>
Fiji meets Papus New Guinea on Saturday morning and takes on
Argentina in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
With its national team making debut appearance at the Hong Kong
event, China was no match to the experienced Samoan side, Cup
winner here in 1993. The Chinese lost its opening match 69-0.
</P>
<P>
China, who began its first ever rugby program just six years
ago, is trying to gain further international experience from the
famed Hong Kong tournament and to prepare for their possible
first-time show at the Asian Games this December in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
All the Chinese players were picked up from the teams of the
Beijing-based China Agricultural University and the People's
Liberationn Army Sports Institute in Guangzhou in South China.
</P>
<P>
"Our players were nervous on playing their first major
tournament of this caliber today and they made really too many
unforced mistakes in the game," said Chinese coach Zheng Hongjun.
</P>
<P>
"We were in a very passive position during the game and were
made exhausted by Samoans' tricky game," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese coach was not expecting a winning chance in their
next game Saturday morning against Tonga, Plate winner at last
year's World Cup meet here. But he hoped to see his side to make
a better performance in their final preliminary match Saturday
afternoon against Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The single round-robin play in fact gave Fiji some pleasant
time to warm-up as it had been pooled into Group C, with
comparatively easy opponents Argentina, Papua New Guinea and
Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
But in their way to the crown might be the powerful All Blacks
team from New Zealand, winner of the Cup two years ago.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand, with six Cup wins to its credit, proved to be too
strong for the Singaporeans in their opening match on Friday. New
Zealander Brad Flemming opened the score with his try 43 seconds
into the first half and the team led 33-0 at the interval.
</P>
<P>
The All Blacks increased the lead in the second half through
their swift and powerful attempts to sealing up the match by a
big-margined triumph.
</P>
<P>
Five-time Cup winner Australia downed Sri Lanka 59-0 in their
first-day match.
</P>
<P>
Host Hong Kong SAR, runner-up in the Plate tournament at last
year's World Cup meet, downed Japan 33-7 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Winners of the six preliminary groups of four and the best two
runners-up advance to the top-class Cup tournament on Sunday. The
four remaining runners-up and the top four third-placed sides go
to the second-ranked Plate tournament, while the eight remaining
teams play in the Bowl tournament, both on the tournament's
closing day on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
