<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barre Calls for Better Way to Fight FN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Former French Prime Minister
Raymond Barre Friday called on the mainstream right wing to seek a
better way to fight the far-right National Front (FN).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Le Figaro, Barre said that the Gaullist
Rally for the Republic and Union for French Democracy (UDF) should
do better in the fields which the FN is taking advantage of, such
as illegal immigration and crimes.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is important to fight in a systematic way by
showing the unrealistic nature of its stands, stressing the harm
to France, and working on a number of themes being exploited by
FN, such as the control of immigration, security, and by making a
more efficient policy," said Barre.
</P>
<P>
The FN rocked the right-wing opposition in the regional
elections on March 15 when five UDF politicians accepted its votes
in the election of council presidents.
</P>
<P>
Barre expressed his reservation over the idea of banning FN,
pointing out that such a move could greatly increase the sympathy
for the far-right.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult in a democratic country to ban ... a
party which respects the rules of public order," he said. "What I
fear is that a banning will result in a surge of votes in favor of
the extreme-right."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his opposition to the alliance between FN and
five UDF politicians, saying: "The end does not justify means."
</P>
<P>
Two of the five UDF regional presidents elected with FN votes
have sice resigned. Pressure is mounting on Charles Millon, the
president of regional council of Rhone-Alpes. But Jacques Blanc,
president of the council in French Catalonia, has vowed to remain
in his post.
</P>
<P>
Barre, who is a close friend of Millon's, said in the interview
that he could not understand why Millon accepted FN votes, and
estimated that a resignation would be a necessary clarification
of the confusion caused by what he called a major fault.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview on Thursday, former French President
Valery Giscard D'Estaing, the founder of UDF, refused to criticize
Millon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textile Official: Smooth Arrangement for Laid-off Workers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Textile workers declared
redundant as a result of restructuring will not create major
contradictions, according to Xu Kunyuan, vice-chairman of the
China National Textile Council (CNTC).
</P>
<P>
Xu said that effective measures introduced by both the central
government and various local governments will ensure the proper
relocation of workers.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has decided to promote breakthroughs in
invigorating medium- and large-sized state-owned enterprises by
slashing the excessive production capacity of the cotton spinning
industry. Over the next three years, 10 million obsolete spindles
will be destroyed and 1.2 million workers will be relocated. The
country plans to relocate 600,000 redundant workers this year.
</P>
<P>
Central government officials point out the most difficult
aspect involved in the restructuring effort will center on making
proper arrangements for redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
Xu stressed that restructuring will be carried out in a planned
manner, with related efforts focusing on coastal areas and major
cities.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of redundant workers in the aforementioned
areas will be greater than in less developed inland and remote
area.
</P>
<P>
The work on relocating laid-off workers will exert pressure on
society since they will be concentrated in terms of both geography
and time periods, according to official with the Labor Department
in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
She said that the coordinated efforts of the government,
society, enterprises and workers will effectively solve related
problems.
</P>
<P>
CNTC liaison officials dispatched to provinces throughout the
nation, including the coastal provinces of Zhejiang, Shandong and
Jiangsu, as well as Tianjin and Shanghai have achieved concrete
progress in relocating redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
Financial subsidies for cotton mills involved in the spindle
reduction effort have been distributed in a timely manner. For
example, the Zhoushan Cotton Mill in Zhejiang received 1.5 million
yuan in subsidies last week on the very day it dismantled some
10,000 cotton spindles last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fertilizer Consumption Rises in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Fertilizer consumption in
Ethiopia has shown a marked progress over the past few years as
more farmers realized the advantages of the input, the National
Fertilizer Industry Agency said.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of the agency, Zeleke Desalegne told local
journalists Friday that 25-30 percent of the Ethiopian farmers
now use fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
He said annual fertilizer consumption was limited to 3,500
tons between 1959 and 1964 and the consumption has now zoomed
following the expansion in the agricultural extension program.
</P>
<P>
Zeleke said over 325,000 tons of fertilizers has been imported
this year, and among them, fifty-five percent of the fertilizers
is imported by the government and the remaining 45 percent by
private importers.
</P>
<P>
He said 95 percent of the fertilizers is used to cultivate
teff, wheat, barley and maize.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia plans to import 368,000 tons of fertilizers this
year. It imported 320,000 tons and 270,000 tons of fertilizers in
1996 and 1995 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textile Official: Smooth Arrangement for Laid-off Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local governments have established reemployment projects and
relocated redundant workers through numerous channels.
</P>
<P>
The Zhoushan Mill has used various channels to relocate 680
redundant workers. For example, the mill has transferred a number
of workers to a subsidiary electronic products plant, encouraged
others to resign and seek employment on their own, dismissed
contract workers, granted early retirements and sent various
people to other enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The nation's major cities have established reemployment centers
for redundant textile workers. Reemployment centers in Shanghai
have helped 210,000 workers find new jobs over the past two
years. The centers plan to provide services for an additional
100,000 workers during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang plans to establish a computer network linking
reemployment centers in various localities. The new network is
expected to enable the centers to improve efficiency in finding
new jobs for workers.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have set minimum wages and subsistence
allowances to support redundant workers facing difficulties. Local
governments also guarantee medical and pension insurance for
workers and ensures that either a husband or wife remains employed.
</P>
<P>
Xu pointed to the difficult tasks related to restructuring
the textile industry and downsizing the work force.
</P>
<P>
Textile enterprises employ over 1.8 million people, or close to
20 percent of the total number of employees working for the
loss-making large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have set goals of providing proper
arrangements for a fixed number of redundant textile workers in
each of the next three years. They will also place priority on
reemploying textile workers.
</P>
<P>
CNTC officials noted that successfully restructuring the
textile industry will provide valuable experience for the reform
of all other medium to large state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
