<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Plans to Offer Shelter for Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean capital of Seoul
has announced plans to provide accommodation for "street dwellers"
whose number is rising due to country's economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
The municipality announced its plans after Acting Mayor Kang
Deok-ki Wednesday inspected outdoor shelters frequented by the
homeless, including high-way underpasses.
</P>
<P>
The city proposes to convert a four-story state-owned building,
formerly used as a worker's welfare center, into a homeless
shelter.
</P>
<P>
The municipality will soon begin talks with the Ministry of
Finance and Economy, the current owner of the downtown building.
</P>
<P>
Some of the street dwellers are genuinely homeless, while a
number are too shy to go home after losing jobs or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
As of the end of last month, more than 1.2 million people were
unemployed because of a severe slowdown of domestic demand,
corporate financial troubles and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world, was
hit by a serious financial crisis produced by corporate
bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institution in late
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
