<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Foreign Exchange Reserve Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign exchange
reserve rose an average 100 million U.S. dollars each day this
month to hit 21.77 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total on March 25 was up from February's 18.54 billion
dollars, the Ministry of Finance and Economy announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The figure, just above the ministry's target of 20 billion
dollars by the end of this month, met the requirements of the
International Monetary Fund in an agreement with South Korea last
December after its financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
With a loan of two billion dollars from the International Bank
for Reconstruction and Development at the end of this month, South
Korean foreign exchange holdings are likely to exceed 24 billion
dollars before April.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserve has been on a steady
rise after hitting a record low of 7.26 billion dollars last
November.
</P>
<P>
The reserve grew to 12.36 billion dollars in January after the
country signed the agreement with the IMF for a rescue loan of 57
billion dollars last December.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the steady growth of the foreign exchange
reserve to increased trade surplus in the past three months and the
smooth inflow of funds from the IMF and other international
institutions.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, which plans to increase its foreign currency
reserve to 40.7 billion dollars by the end of this year, will
issue state bonds valued at three billion dollars in the United
States and Europe beginning April 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
