<HEADLINE> U.S. Automakers Urge South Korea to Lower Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. automakers have appealed
to South Korea to lower its tariffs on imported U.S. automobiles
and revise its tariff system on engine capacity.
</P>
<P>
General Motors, Ford and Chrysler made the appeal on Friday
when their representatives met Lee Tae-shik, director of the
Regional Trade Bureau of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
They urged South Korea to cut the tariff on limousines by 2.5
percent from the current eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came just before another round of talks between
South Korea and the United States on freeing up the South Korean
auto market, scheduled for the next month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. automakers complained that South Korea's current
tariff system, which imposes heavy duties on large engine limousines,
apparently discriminates against foreign automobiles. South Korean
cars are usually equipped with small engines.
</P>
<P>
But South Korea has insisted that its limousine tariff of eight
percent is much lower than that of the European Union member
states.
</P>
<P>
South Korea plans to revise its imported auto tariff system
based on engine capacity which was made in accordance with its
road conditions, traffic safety, environment and tax revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
