<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's National Drug Abuse Forum Inaugurated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A national drug abuse forum for
Kenya was inaugurated Friday in response to growing drug abuse in
the country and to mark the U.N. General Assembly special session
on Drugs to be held in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Koli Kouame, representative of the Regional Office for East
and Southern Africa of the U.N. International Drug Control
Program (UNDCP) told a press conference here on Friday that UNDCP
fully supported the forum.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the establishment of the Kenya
forum would serve as a precursor to the formation of other forum
chapters in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that the inaugural meeting would bring together more
than 50 non-governmental organizations, nine student associations
and a number of concerned private groups and individuals.
</P>
<P>
A community-wide participatory and partnership approach is
crucial to the accurate assessment of the drug problem and to
addressing the need for the provision of prevention and treatment
programs, the U.N. official stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kouame told reporters that an experts meeting held here
between March 17 and March 19 drafted an African common position
on drug control which was expected to form the core statements by
high-level African officials who would attend the U.N. special
session.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. special session will focus on six
specific topics, namely the control of chemical precursors,
amphetamine-type stimulants, judicial cooperation, money
laundering, drug demand reduction and elimination of illicit
crops.
</P>
<P>
According to Kouame, the amphetamine-type stimulants (ATS) are
the principal synthetic drugs manufactured clandestinely and a
wave of synthetic stimulant abuse has been reported in recent
years with a 16-percent average annual increase of quantity
seized from 1978 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
Kouame noted that as some 30 million people consume ATS
throughout the world now, the U.N. special session would give
higher priority to the subject and adopt an "Action Plan Against
Manufacture, Trafficking and Abuse of ATS and Their Precursors".
</P>
</TEXT>
