<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mauritius Tops Africa Competitiveness List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Mauritius heads the list of
competitiveness in 23 African countries, according to a report of
the World Economic Forum (WEF).
</P>
<P>
The list features in the Africa Competitiveness Report 1998
published by WEF with the Harvard Institute of International
Development, said a WEF press release received here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius, the report says, has made great strides since
gaining independence 30 years ago and has become one of the
region's most vibrant economies.
</P>
<P>
Averaging an annual six percent growth rate, the country is
also cited as one of the best offshore locations for business. It
has an export-led growth program spearheaded by a well-functioning
export processing zone.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia, second on the list, has had an average growth of 4.5
percent over the past decade. With a real gross domestic product
of just under 14 billion U.S. dollars, Tunisia's economy is four
times larger than either Botswana or Mauritius. Tunisia is looking
towards increasing trade centered on agreements with the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, upon achieving independence, was classified as one of
the world's most impoverished countries. Three decades later, the
country has become a solid member of the World Bank's group of
middle income countries. Its GDP of 4.6 percent is Africa's third
largest.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's successful attempts at healing the wounds of its
recent war have pushed it to fourth place. Its export-oriented
economy, good infrastructure and membership in the Southern
African Customs Union has assured the country of a modest two
percent per capita growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Although South Africa ranks seventh, the report points out, it
has the continent's largest economy. It has shown tremendous
performance in making a peaceful transition to democratic rule.
While growth in economic terms has not been particularly high, the
nation has maintained stability under circumstances which most
observers had expected would lead to civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
As a special project within the framework of the WEF's Global
Competitiveness Report, the Africa Competitiveness Report 1998 is
the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
Incorporated since 1971 as a foundation, the Geneva-based WEF
is an independent and non-profit organization. It has a
consultative status with the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
