<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Foreign Debt Hits 11 Billion U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's foregin debt hit
about 11 billion U.S. dollars, much of which has been accumulated
due to interests, the daily Noticias quoted a government official
as saying on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Graeme Saul, member of the government group dealing with
foreign debt, said that the heavy burden of its foreign debt has
seriously hindered the growth of Mozambique's economy and the
improvement of people's living.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to considerably
reduce Mozambique's debt.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of Mozambique's debt, or 7.453 billion U.S.
dollars, has been borrowed from the Paris Club which groups
Russia, Italy, France, Germany, Portugal and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The debt owed to Russia is some 2.5 billion U.S. dollars,
largely resulting from Mozambique's purchase of the Russian
military materials in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Mmultilateral debt reaches about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars,
which includes 850 million U.S. dollars owed to the World Bank,
some 180 millions U.S. dollars to the International Monetary Fund
and the same amount to the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has a bilateral debt of about 730 million U.S.
dollars, which is mainly owed to sixteen countries outside the
Paris Club, such as Algeria, Libya and Angola.
</P>
<P>
About 930 million U.S. Dollars are of commercial debts for the
construction of the Cahora Bassa Hydroelectric Power Station.
Though constructed, the station in which Mozambique owns 18
percent of its shares, has never generated any electricity for a
variety of reasons, only leaving a debt of about 3.2 billion U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Facing Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Friday called upon the people to save water at a
time when the water shortage problem has affected various states
including the capital city of Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the water problem was related to the change in
the climatic situation in Malaysia and the most effective way was
for everyone to save water and be thrifty.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was commenting on the on-going drought and
the problem of water supply in several states including Selangor,
Negeri Sembilan, Malacca and Pulau Pinang.
</P>
<P>
The government is already implementing several programs to
overcome the water problem and would take about five months to
complete, Mahathir said in Jitra in the northern state of Kedah
after a political party function, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said his deputy Anwar Ibrahim will chair a meeting of
representatives of the relevant authorities to find a solution to
the water problem which is becoming increasingly critical.
</P>
<P>
The water problem was more serious in Klang Valley covering
Kuala Lumpur and its surrounding areas where, according to reports
of the national newspapers, some 300,000 residents have been
affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
