<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Living Standards Hit New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The living standards of China's
urbanites have basically reached a benchmark level featuring rising
incomes and significant changes in the consumption mix, according
to the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
A recent SSB survey placed the average 1997 urban income
level at 5,160 yuan (632.53 US dollars), up a dramatic 155 percent
on the 1992 figure, with the average annual increase standing at
20.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rising income levels were accompanied by major changes in the
consumption mix. The SSB report indicated a downward trend in the
proportion of expenditures on food, garments and household
appliances in recent years, with a sharp increase in spending on
education, culture activities, entertainment, medical and health
care, transportation, telecommunications and housing.
</P>
<P>
Last year's per capita spending for transportation and
telecommunications stood at 233 yuan, 5.3 times the figure for
1992 and a level topping all other consumption categories.
</P>
<P>
Per capita expenditures on medical and health care stood at 180
yuan, an 3.3-fold rise on 1992. Estimated education expenditures
were placed at 238 yuan, a dramatic 270 percent rise over the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, of every 100 urban families, 54 owned their
own homes wholly or partly, 69 lived in apartments with at least
two bedrooms, 59 used gas for cooking and 69 had telephones.
</P>
<P>
The government reform plan calls for the overall national
average to reach "basically well-off" standards by the year 2000.
</P>
