<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian PM Vows to Stay in Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Victor
Ciorbea has defied mounting pressure within the government and
declared that he will not resign.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded statement, Ciorbea said Thursday he was
acting for the "stability of the nation".
</P>
<P>
He had been recommended for the post by the coalition and
approved by the parliament and president, he added.
</P>
<P>
Those wanting him to resign would have to go through the legal
channels by staging a no-confidence vote of his government,
otherwise he would not tender his resignation, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Romania's governing coalition has been in turmoil since early
this year, as the second largest partner of the coalition, the
Democratic Party, lost confidence in Ciorbea who belongs to the
Christian Democrat National Peasants' Party.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party called on Ciorbea's government to resign
by the end of March and withdrew from the coalition in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
