<HEADLINE> WEF Pushes for Africa's Integration into Global Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- President of the World Economic
Forum (WEF) Klaus Schwab has said the integration of Africa into
the global economy was "one of the greatest challenges in the 21st
century".
</P>
<P>
Schwab made the remarks in his preface to the Africa
Competitiveness Report 1998, published recently by the WEF in
collaboration with the Harvard Institute of International
Development, according to a WEF press release.
</P>
<P>
"The World Economic Forum has been spearheading efforts to
provide African entrepreneurs and business leaders from South
Africa to Egypt with the opportunity of building a strong
business-driven network through which private sector-led economic
development can rapidly take place," Schwab said.
</P>
<P>
As a special project within the framework of the WEF's Global
Competitiveness Report, the Africa Competitiveness Report 1998 is
the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
Incorporated since 1971 as a foundation, the Geneva-based WEF
is an independent and non-profit organization. It has a
consultative status with the United Nations. 
</P>
