<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.5 Percent Pay Rise Proposed for German Public Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany's 3.2 million public sector
workers could be in line for a 1.5 percent pay rise from January
1 of this year.
</P>
<P>
The rise was recommended early Friday after negotiations
between mediators, trade unions and employers, but it still needs
to be reviewed by trade unions, which will make a final decision
on April 2.
</P>
<P>
It was also proposed that the wage level of public service
employees in eastern Germany should be raised by 1.5 percent from
September 1 to 86.5 percent of that of their fellow workers in the
west, and stay there till December 1999.
</P>
<P>
The pay dispute was brought to arbitration earlier this month
after talks broke down between federal, state, and municipal
governments and Germany's two major public service trade unions,
DAG and OeTV.
</P>
<P>
DAG and OeTV rejected the employers' offer of a one percent
increase. They had been demanding a 4.5 percent pay rise and
organized strikes for higher wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
The strikes had disrupted public services such as transport,
garbage collection and health clinics across the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
