<HEADLINE> German BMW Confirms Bid for British Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn, March 25 (Xinhua) -- German carmaker BMW confirmed Friday
that it has bid for the British luxuxy carmaker Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Munich-based BMW said the bid was tabled
Wednesday, one day after German rival Volkswagen (VW) made an
offer.
</P>
<P>
Like VW, BMW did not disclose financial details of the bid.
</P>
<P>
British press reports said Rolls-Royce's parent company Vickers
engineering group wished to sell Rolls for at least 300 million pounds
(502 million U.S. dollars), compared to a value of 250 million pounds
(419 million dollars) estimated by bidders.
</P>
<P>
Crewe-based Rolls-Royce was put up for sale by Vickers earlier
this year. BMW, which makes the V12 engine for Rolls, is seen as
having a better chance than Europe's largest carmaker VW.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times reported that Kevin Morley, Rolls-Royce's
former director and a group of "Rolls-Royce enthusiasts" has also
joined the bidding, fearing the loss of the right to the brand
name Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
The name belongs to the Rolls-Royce aero-engine company, to which
the luxury carmaker was once a division. The aero-engine company's
contract of sale of the carmaker confirms its claim to the brand name,
in case of a takeover by foreign buyers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
