<HEADLINE> Mandela: I Won't Betray Friends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela reiterated Friday that he would not betray friends
who had helped the country in the apartheid era, such as Libya,
Iran and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with visiting United States
President Bill Clinton, Mandela said he had high respect for
Clinton, but they were "not without differences" on some issues.
</P>
<P>
He said that South Africa had received heads of state from all
over the world, including Cuban President Fidel Castro, former
Iranian President Hojatoleslam Rafsanjani and Libyan leader
Muammar Gadaffi.
</P>
<P>
These people were South Africans' friends who had helped them
in the darkest days in South Africa's history by providing the
resources they needed to win, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to betray the trust of those who helped us,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations charter called upon all member
states to settle differences by means of negotiation and the
United States, a world superpower, should set an example for the
rest of the world in this regard.
</P>
<P>
One of the reasons that the world highly appreciated South
Africa's success was that South Africans were able to sit down
with their enemies and talk about reconciliation, Mandela noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mandela and Clinton held one-on-one talks for more
than an hour, and then were joined by members of their respective
cabinets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
