<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Cattle Threatened by Fatal Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A fatal cattle disease has
made an evil comeback in Tanzania, causing heavy deaths to herds,
agriculture experts said.
</P>
<P>
The disease, known as Contagious Bovine Pleuropneumonia
(CBPP), has killed more than 40,000 cattle in Tanzania over the
past eight years as it is spreading in east African countries.
</P>
<P>
The disease has affected 13 regions in Tanzania, said Peter
Msolla, Deputy Vice-Chancellor of the Sokoine University of
Agriculture (SUA), adding that Tanzania has been unable to
control the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanians eradicated the disease in 1967, but it has
resurfaced in the country since 1990, Msolla told a training
course Thursday at the university, based in the central Morogoro
Region.
</P>
<P>
CBPP, along with other cattle diseases, has posed dangers to
human health and threatened food security system in the country,
Msolla was quoted by The Guardian newspaper as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Other countries also affected by CBPP are Kenya, Rwanda,
Uganda, Burundi and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has a high population of cattle, ranking the third
after Sudan and Ethiopia in Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
