capital belong to private investors and financial and insurance
institutions in Morocco, the Gulf states and the United States.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab authority for investment and agricultural
development has expressed readiness to finance new Egyptian
agricultural projects to be submitted by the Cairo government,
particularly in the fields of edible oil production, export and
marketing of agricultural crops.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi-based authority had at a recent meeting in Dubai
expressed its appreciation of the progress in a sugar production
project at the Egyptian province of Fayoum, some 120 kilometers
south of Cairo. The authority contributes 17 percent of the some
60 million-dollar project with a production capacity of about
120,000 tonnes of sugar from sugar-beets a year.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi company of land transportation has
announced a 44 percent cut in its losses in 1997, reaching 1.1
million U.S. dollars as compared to a 1.94 million-dollar-loss in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The general manager of the company Youssef Mohamed Bakhsh has
attributed the decrease in losses to a cut in operational and
maintenance expenses and further control in expenses.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- The Kuwaiti shares index has somewhat improved over
the past week ending Wednesday on account of the rise in world oil
prices and the formation of a new cabinet. Likewise, the Kuwaiti
stock exchange market has gone up by 9.6 points during the week
ending Wednesday, closing at 2329.4 points. 
</P>
