<HEADLINE> Clinton, Mandela Get Down to Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Pomp and ceremony will give
way to business Friday when U.S. President Bill Clinton holds
formal talks with President Nelson Mandela in Cape Town on the
second day of his visit.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will also hold a joint press conference in
Mandela's residence, before flying aboard the U.S. presidential
helicopter to Robben island, home to Mandela and other political
prisoners under apartheid.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral talks are expected to cover some contentious
issues, including South Africa's problems with Clinton's Africa
Trade Bill.
</P>
<P>
Clinton may also try to persuade Mandela to bring South Africa
into an international anti-corruption initiative, while Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo hinted Thursday that his government will not
bring up the American proposals for African Crisis Response
Initiative and for an African peace keeping force with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Nzo told reporters that such an initiative can only be
discussed by the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Later in the evening, 750 guests will descend on the Verrest
Wine Estate for a state banquet in Clinton's honor.
</P>
<P>
Although there would be no formal presentation of South
Africa's highest honor to Clinton, Mandela would hand over the
Order of Good Hope privately to the U.S. President after the
banquet, a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On how Clinton would feel on accepting the award-- he will
share it with his arch foe Libyan leader Muammar Gathafi and
others -- White House spokesman Mike Meeurry said it had been
given to a range of individuals and "the President will accept it
in the spirit in which it is given."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived in Cape Town Thursday morning for a
Four-day state visit to South Africa, will leave the city
Saturday morning for Johannesburg where he will visit black
township of Soweto and meet young community and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
He will embark on the penultimate leg of his six-nation
African tour with a visit to Botswana Sunday.  
</P>
