<HEADLINE> HK Civil Servants to Aid Work of Subsector Polling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2,200 Hong Kong
civil servants will be organized to assist the work related to
polling stations and vote counting for the Election Committee
subsector elections scheduled to be held here on April 2.
</P>
<P>
The Registration and Electoral Office are holding several
briefing sessions for the civil servants on the arrangement and
procedures of the elections.
</P>
<P>
About 140,000 voters from 31 subsectors representing various
trades, professions, labor and social service sectors, and
district-based organizations will cast their votes on the polling
day to elect their representatives on the Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
A total of 963 candidates will compete for 588 seats.
</P>
<P>
The 588 members, together with 95 members already returned from
four uncontested subsectors, 77 ex-officio members and 40
representatives nominated by the religious subsector, will form an
800-strong Election Committee. The Election Committee will then
elect 10 Legislative Council members on May 24.
</P>
<P>
According to the Registration and Electoral Office, 90 polling
stations will be open throughout Hong Kong from 7.30 AM to 10.30
PM on April 2.
</P>
<P>
The counting of votes will be done by computers as soon as
ballot boxes are delivered to a central counting station to be set
up at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region will mobilize more than 10,000 staff members
to participate in the work of the first Legislative Council
Election scheduled to be held on May 24.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council will be composed of 60 members with 20
to be returned from the geographical constituency, 10 from the
Election Committee and 30 from the functional constituency.
</P>
</TEXT>
