<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Tighten Emission Standards for Diesel Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government said
Friday that it will introduce more stringent emission standards
for first registration of diesel private cars and light duty
vehicles in a bid to reduce the air pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
Under an amended air pollution control regulation published
Friday, the government upgrades the current emission standards for
diesel vehicles of four tons and below, to come in line with the
latest European Union emission standards.
</P>
<P>
These new standards will reduce emissions of respirable
suspended particulates, and nitrogen oxides and hydrocarbons from
individual diesel vehicles by 55 percent and 38 percent
respectively, a government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Similar stringent emission standards for diesel vehicles of
four tons and above had already been applied since April 1, 1997,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new standards were so stringent that it would
in practice prevent future registration of diesel private cars in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The new emission standards for private diesel cars will come
into effect on April 1, 1998 while those for light duty diesel
vehicles will be implemented on October 1, 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
