<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Development Strategy Issued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) has worked out a long-term
land-transport-environmental planning framework to enable Hong
Kong to continue to grow as a regional and international "City of
Vision."
</P>
<P>
According to a report available here Friday, the strategy has
also taken account of the development trends in South China,
especially in the Pearl River Delta.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Territorial Development Strategy Review
-- a Response to Change and Challenges," assumes four broad time
frames as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- The Short Term up to 2001: to focus on the speediest
possible implementation of individual projects already in the
pipeline, especially with regard to housing;
</P>
<P>
-- The Medium Term from 2001 to 2006: to accelerate the
detailed design and implementation of already planned larger-scale
land development and related infrastructure projects on a more
coordinated basis, as many of the land development projects are
required for housing;
</P>
<P>
-- The Long Term from 2006 to 2011: to promulgate and complete
as soon as possible a number of integrated planning and
development studies for additional strategic growth areas to
provide a framework for the subsequent implementation of priority
projects; and
</P>
<P>
-- An Extended Time Horizon beyond 2011: to set new strategic
development concepts in the context of future development
scenarios anticipated by the Commission on Strategic Development
of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
In formulating the strategic development options, the report
pointed out, two broad regional development scenarios were
initially assumed, with the first scenario postulating that the
Pearl River Delta will be the major economic hinterland of Hong
Kong over the long term. The second scenario postulates that
Guangdong Province and other inner provinces of the mainland will
be the major economic hinterland of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the strategy, Secretary for Planning, Environment
and Land Bowen Leung Po-wing stressed on Thursday: "We can no
longer make plans in isolation." The experts and officials of both
the SAR and the mainland are working through various committees to
deal with a number of large-scale projects, he added.
</P>
<P>
The primary goal of the strategy is "to establish a broad,
long-term land use-transport-environmental planning framework
within which the necessary land and infrastructure can be
provided, having regard to resources availability," Leung said. It
is "to enable Hong Kong to continue to grow as a regional and
international 'City of Vision' and to maintain and enhance its
image as an attractive place in which to live and work, taking
account of development trends in South China, especially in the
Pearl River Delta." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Enhance Role As Major Financial Center: Official (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary of the Hong
 Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Donald Tsang Friday
stressed the need to enhance the SAR's role as a major financial
center in the world and defend the linked exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the "Asian Investment Conference," Tsang said that
the effect of the "Asian Contagion," or the recent financial
turmoil, on Hong Kong had been painful, but by no means critical,
nor chronic.
</P>
<P>
"We must maintain and enhance Hong Kong's role as a major
financial center in the region and internationally," he said. "We
are determined to defend the linked exchange rate system (between
the HK and U.S. dollars) at the present level of parity."
</P>
<P>
Tsang said the financial turmoil sweeping some East Asian
economies had given Hong Kong an opportunity to critically assess
its own "battle conditions."
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's GDP (Gross Domestic Product) growth may
slow down, but its a long history of fiscal discipline will help
the government "forge ahead with massive spending on
infrastructure, education and housing" despite the downturn.
</P>
<P>
Property prices in Hong Kong had now dropped to a more
realistic level, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's tourism is down, "but that has provided us with the
 impetus to seek out and develop new markets," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The relatively high interest rates are expected to soften once
the financial turmoil in Asia calms down and "speculators finally
realize they cannot bet against the HK dollar and win," he
stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Enhance Role As Major Financial Center: Official (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his address, Tsang gave his first-hand observations of a
review of the banking and stock market systems conducted recently
by the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The review confirmed that Hong Kong's banking system was
generally well-regulated and banks well-managed.
</P>
<P>
"But we must not be complacent and will need to reinforce our
efforts to ensure banks pay special attention to the quality of
their assets to limit exposure in those areas affected by interest
rate volatility," the financial secretary said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was also satisfied with the regulatory framework of
the securities and futures markets.
</P>
<P>
With a view to reducing market volatility as well as providing
greater protection to investors and shareholders, Tsang said, he
was looking at areas such as derivative trading, notably index
futures and derivative warrants, as well as borrowing and
short-selling stocks.
</P>
<P>
He said the review report to be unveiled next month would
bolster the investing public's confidence in the financial and
securities markets.
</P>
<P>
Taking a more macro view of the Asian financial crisis, Tsang
observed that while Hong Kong was undeniably part of Asia, its
systems were different from those in other Asian economies and
"have protected us from contracting the full-blown financial flu
which has swept through the region."
</P>
<P>
"I think, if anything, Hong Kong represents a model of economic
management others in Asia are now realizing they should try to
follow: a free market under the rule of law; a clean government
which believes in prudent financial management and in not
directing the economy; a well-regulated and well-managed financial
sector; a reputation for playing by the rules; openness and
accountability," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 institutional investors and fund managers from
all over the world attended the three-day conference at the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center. The meeting, organized by
the Credit Suisse First Boston, opened on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
