<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Calls for Expanded Peaceful Use of Nuclear Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientist Yan Shuheng
said today that China needs to expand the peaceful use of nuclear
resources to ensure that its nuclear power industry reaches
advanced world levels.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power is the major component of the peaceful use of
nuclear resources, said Yan, secretary-general of the Chinese
Nuclear Society. Yan made the remarks during ceremonies marking
the conclusion of an international nuclear industry exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Development of the nuclear power industry is crucial for
coastal areas in south and east China which face shortages of
coal, oil and water resources, said Yan.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of the country's coal mines are located in
north China, while more than 80 percent of the water resources
are found in southwest China. Energy shortages pose a major threat
in highly populated areas in eastern, southern and northeastern
China, home to the nation's major industrial bases.
</P>
<P>
The transportation of coal from north to south China currently
occupies over half of the nation's total railway capacity. Experts
say that additional nuclear power stations in south and east China
could significantly reduce the transportation burden.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear power industry currently generates a mere 1.2
percent of the nation's total power output, a level substantially
lower than the worldwide average of 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power is highly reliable compared with any other energy
resources, said Yan, a scientist engaged in nuclear studies for 40
years.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power station features four protective layers,
including a one-meter thick concrete "safe layer" separating
radioactive matter from surrounding areas, according to Yan.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station of east China's Zhejiang
Province and the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station in south China's
Guangdong Province have operated safely since the early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
