<HEADLINE> Myanmar Reiterates Reconciliation Policy On KNU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 27 (Xinhua)-- The Myanmar government Friday
reiterated that it continues to hold out its "Olive Branch" to all
factions of the Kayin National Union (KNU) as it has done so
successfully with all other former insurgencies of the national
races.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1980s, a dozen anti-government ethnic armed
groups have surrendered to and made peace with the government.
However, the KNU, an anti-government ethnic armed group active on
the Myanmar-Thai border, has still refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
Armed men belonging to the Democratic Kayin Buddhist Army
(DKBA), a breakaway group of the KNU, attacked a Kayin refuge camp
on the Thai-Myanmar border three times this month, according to
Thai media sources.
</P>
<P>
An official information sheet Friday confirmed that a group of
30 armed men of the KNU last Tuesday attacked the War Hpot Kaw
village, 40 km inside Myanmar off the border, burning down 2
houses and wounding 3 villagers.
</P>
<P>
The recent incidents were merely interfactional conflicts
within the separatist KNU, the information sheet said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the policy of the Myanmar Government to encourage
any factions of the KNU to violate the sovereignty of a
neighboring country," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government is fully committed to maintaining good
and friendly relations with all countries in the world,
particularly with its neighbors, it stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
