<HEADLINE> India PM Presents Confidence Motion to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee Friday sought a vote of confidence in his
government in the just constituted lower house of parliament and
appealed for consensus to put an end to political instability in
the country.
</P>
<P>
As directed by President K. R. Narayanan last week, the
Vajpayee government would have to show its majority and obtain
confidence of the House within 10 days after its swearing-in on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
Moving a one-line motion, Vajpayee said he already had the
majority and would prove it.
</P>
<P>
In a 45-minute speech, Vajpayee urged all parties to come
together for tackling national issues. Political instability had
severely affected the country's economy and interests in the last
18 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
Voting on the motion is slated for Saturday after two days of
discussion and debates.
</P>
<P>
Initiating the debate on the confidence motion, Congress senior
leader and opposition leader of the House Sharad Pawar expressed
doubts about the stability plank of the ruling Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP)-led coalition, saying that its vulnerability to
pressure from regional parties and groups was not a reassuring
signal for good governance.
</P>
<P>
The coalition was fraught with internal contradictions and the
BJP and its allies were having different perceptions on several
key issues and conflicting ambitions, analysts said. This renders
the ruling coalition incapable of providing a stable government,
Pawar said.  
</P>
