<HEADLINE> Foreign Donors Dump Expired Drugs in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Many foreign donors are dumping
expired drugs in Uganda, a National Drug Authority (NDA) official
said.
</P>
<P>
Abaasi Kabogo, the Executive Secretary of NDA, reported to
annual Catholic Medical Bureau recently that every metric ton of
expired drugs transported to Uganda saves the donors an average
loss of 2,000 U.S. Dollars in their own countries, the Monitor
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He appealed non-government agencies concerned to avoid such
ill-motivated donations and purchase drugs from reliable local
sources because the latter "is in line with the recommendations
of both the World Health Organization and the World Council of
Churches".
</P>
<P>
Most drugs in use in the country are donations. The sources of
drugs include private individuals, companies, NGOs, UN agencies,
UNOCEF and foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
The most evaluations have repeatedly shown that many of the
medical supplies were not appropriate ones, he said.  
</P>
