<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Speaker Unapologetic in Mavhaire Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Speaker of Parliament
Cyril Ndebele Thursday refused to apologize over his recent
decision that the ruling Zanu (PF) party could not discipline a
parliament member for his utterances in parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a lengthy statement greeted by a hushed and attentive
almost full legislative assembly, Ndebele said the constitution
of Zimbabwe and the privileges, immunities and powers of
parliament act protect all utterances made in parliament or
committees of parliament, the Herald Daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Masvingo central Member of Parliament Dzikamayi Mavhaire, was
last week dismissed from the party's central committee and
suspended from holding any position in the ruling party for two
years following a statement which he made in parliament during
debate on constitutional reforms that President Robert Mugabe
"must go".
</P>
<P>
At the Zanu central committee meeting last Friday, Ndebele and
Mavhaire were rebuked by Mugabe, who said there was an open
rebellion against the ruling party by some top party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said these "evil schemers, conspirators, political
saboteurs" and their "misguided" ambitions were responsible for
the present situation of confusion and anxiety in the party, and
had to be "dealt with once and for all".
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, spokesman of party Nathan Shamuyarira
announced the speaker would be called to explain his decision.
</P>
<P>
"The matter is still under discussion by the disciplinary
committee which will report to the politburo and then to the
central committee."
</P>
<P>
The speaker Thursday said, "it is a privilege known to the law
that a member shall not be liable to any proceedings by reason of
anything which he may have said in parliament." He has reiterated
his loyalty to the party and Mugabe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
