<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspections of Iraqi Presidential Sites Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A group of 20 U.N. arms
inspectors and senior diplomats on Friday continued inspection of
the Iraqi presidential site -- Radwaniyah palace.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors and diplomats left for the southern suburb
of Baghdad where Radwaniyah palace locates in around 25 vans
from the Baghdad Monitoring and Certification Center, or the
Canal Hotel.
</P>
<P>
The inspection of Radwaniyah palace started Thursday, which
lasted about eight hours. Diplomatic sources said inspections went
on very smoothly and the Iraqi side had shown "astonishing
cooperation".
</P>
<P>
Charles Duelfer, an American, deputy chairman of the
U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM on dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction led the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz last month, Iraq
agrees to open its eight presidential sites previously off-limits
to inspections.
</P>
<P>
A special group of senior diplomats appointed by Annan and
arms experts from UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy
Agency, headed by Sri Lankan Jayanatha Dhanapala, was assigned
to carry out the mission.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. map makers, all the eight Iraqi presidential
compounds cover an area of 31.5 square kilometers, including
10 square kilometers of water surface, which have been suspected
of hiding banned weapons of mass destruction and their programs.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler told a press conference in
Baghdad on Sunday there are 1,058 buildings in the eight
presidential compounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
