<HEADLINE> Clinton's Visit to Uganda Hailed as Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The visit of U.S. President to
Uganda is successful, Uganda officials said.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, the State Minister in Presidential Office in
charge of political affairs and the chief of the preparation for
the visit, told the New Vision, a daily newspaper here, that the
west has now realized the importance of Africa as a part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"This is a welcome move which must be exploited," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. signed an investment agreement with Uganda during
Clintons' visit, and Hillary Clinton, the first lady, announced
U.S. will fund Uganda's primary education, women training and
food security programs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president had a two-day state visit to the country on
March 24 to 25 and left for South Africa late March 25.
</P>
<P>
Rebecca Kadaga, the State Minister for Foreign Affairs in
Charge of Regional Cooperation, said her country will do
everything to exploit this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"The visit has opened the door for a working relationship
between the countries in the region on the one hand, and the U.S.
on the other," she said.
</P>
<P>
Hope Kivengere, the Press Secretary to Uganda President Yoweri
Moseveni, also described Clinton's visit as a good opportunity
for the U.S. to get an insight into Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
