<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Introduces Efficient Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Science Commission in
southwest China's Sichuan Province has launched a new irrigation
project to ensure the efficient use of water in dry hilly areas.
</P>
<P>
The project, considered to be a fundamental approach for
solving problems associated with problem, is expected to yield
substantial benefits over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Commission director Yang Guo'an said a contingent of 60-odd
agricultural experts will work on the project to be carried out at
a cost of three million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Yao said the project will ensure efficient irrigation on
between 80-90 percent of experimental fields.
</P>
<P>
Experts point to the importance and necessity for introducing
efficient irrigation system in Sichuan, one of the nation's most
densely populated provinces.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources note that the effective use of Sichuan's
irrigation resources stands at a mere 40 percent. They also note
that the low grain yields on 70 percent of China's farm land can
be attributed to water shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
