<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Museum Displays the Age of Dinosaurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A new display hall in east
China's Zhejiang Province has enabled local residents, mostly
children, to experience the world of dinosaurs some 65 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The curator of the Zhejiang Museum of Natural History notes the
display hall highlights 2,000 rare examples of the museum's total
collection of over 80,000 items, including the skeletal remains of
a 12 meter gray whale, the largest ever found in china, and the
fossilized remains of the famous Confucius Bird.
</P>
<P>
The hall's six sections, which include exhibitions of
dinosaurs, marine animals and the history of geology, trace the
evolution of lower animals.
</P>
<P>
One exhibit area, which covers 600 sq.m. and features
cobblestones and artifical rockery rather than glass cabinets,
provides visitors with a clear and unobstructed view of items on
display, according to the curator.
</P>
<P>
The museum plans to offer new exhibits every six months and
visitors will be allowed to join in scientific demonstrations. The
curator noted that related "activities will spark the curiosity
and interest of children and will greatly enhance learning in the
area of science."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
