<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Eurobonds Succeeds in International Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has succeeded in an
unprecedented borrowing drive as its Eurobonds issues are welcomed
in the international markets, the Daily Star newspaper said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese, Arab, and Western investors are rushing to buy the
country's two Eurobonds issues worth of 800 million U.S. dollars,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese government is selling 300 million dollars five-year
and 500 million dollars three-year bonds through Paribas, a
French bank. Together they make for the Arab world's largest
issue.
</P>
<P>
Paribas is marketing the bonds through "roadshow," a series
of presentations that move from country to country. They
explain the appeal of the bonds, and compare them to other
investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The roadshow kicked off in the Switzerland on Thursday, it
proceeds to the United Kingdom Friday and moves on the Bahrain
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Lebanese central bank official said the Finance Ministry
and the bank may consider raising the Eurobonds to 1 billion
U.S. dollars as the roadshow in Europe proved to be such a
success.
</P>
<P>
The two offerings, which will bring to nearly 2 billion
dollars, the amount the government has raised in Eurobonds
since 1994, aims at offsetting part of the country's huge
internal debt in Lebanese pound by the foreign currency which
averagely carries an interest rate of about 9 percent, less
than half the domestic borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's public debt was closing at 15 billion dollars in
January this year, of which only 2.4 billion dollars was
external.
</P>
<P>
The government also intends, through outside borrowing, to
bring under control the ballooning budget deficit that reached
18 percent of the Gross Domestic Product last year.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's ability to tap international markets has been in
question after international rating agencies, such as Standard &AMP;
Poor, warned of a possible downgrade if Lebanese government
failed to bring down the deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Rates in Thailand </HEADLINE>
