<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Thursday launched a
"tripartite cooperation" with French President Jacques Chirac and
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in Moscow. Symbolically, the three
leaders recast Europe by giving Russia a prince's place in a
Greater Europe. "The Greater Europe will be hegemonic, because
Russia will adhere to it," said Yeltsin after the summit.
</P>
<P>
-- After a brief stop in Rwanda, U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday began his state visit in South Africa where he will
express a great optimism over the future of Africa. "You offered
the most convincing example of victory over the division of the
past," Clinton told the South African parliament in Capetown,
prior to a highly covered summit between him and Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Le Figaro, former French Prime Minister
 Raymond Barre expressed his support to the initiative by the
president of Democratic Force party, Francois Bayrou, to establish
a new centrist party to replace the Union for French Democracy
(UDF). Barre, who is now Mayor of Lyon, estimated that the UDF
"could not survive long," while expressing his hope that former
Defense Minister Charles Millon will resign from his post as
president of the regional council of Rhone-Alpes, which he won
with the support of the National Front.
</P>
<P>
-- A delegation of French employers will arrive in Algeria on
Friday on a visit marking Paris' return to the Algerian market
which has become more and more competitive between Europeans and
Americans. 
