<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cultural Contacts Bridge Sino-Austrian Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Austrian painter Max Weiler's
exhibition on display in the China Art Gallery shows vivid and
unique landscapes to the Chinese and adds bright color to cultural
contacts between China and Austria.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and Austrian Vice-Chancellor
and Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel attended the opening
ceremony on March 10. The exhibition was part of the "98 China
Year of International Fine Arts" series.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel noted that the exhibition will help to bridge
understanding between the two countries and contribute to
Sino-Austrian cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He noted that future exhibitions and concerts are now under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people visited the exhibition every day. They
praised the charm of Weiler's works.
</P>
<P>
Weiler, 88, has long cherished the idea of exhibiting his works
in China, The Austrian painter identifies himself with principles
in Chinese landscape paintings dating to the Song Dynasty
(960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The artist integrates Chinese styles with modern European
abstract art to create stylish paintings.
</P>
<P>
Health problems prevented Weiler from attending the opening
ceremony. However, a personal diary notation explains that his
creativity is a spiritual one that sparks disquieting thoughts and
such thoughts surge from the vast stretches of China to the
mountains of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
China's Central Nationalities Orchestra (CNO) presented the
charm of Chinese music in the "Golden Hall" of Vienna on the eve
of the Year of the Tiger.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin sent a congratulatory message
noting that the orchestra's performances will undoubtedly enhance
Austrian and European understanding of China's long history,
culture and traditional national music, and will also benefit
friendly cultural contacts between countries throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian music critic who hosted the concert pointed to the
shining ties link between China, the "Golden Hall" and Strauss.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (VPO) performed in China in
October 1996. The Vienna Strauss Holiday Orchestra has also
presented vivid performances in China and the CNO performed in the
"Golden Hall" on the eve of this year's Spring Festival, the major
traditional Chinese holiday. All these exchange performances have
further enhanced dialog between the Chinese and western cultures.
</P>
<P>
Both President Jiang Zemin and Austrian President Thomas
Klestil once described music as an important means for conveying
Sino-Austrian friendship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
