<HEADLINE> China Developing Nuclear Power To Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China has started work on four
large nuclear power stations, which are expected to increase the
proportion of power coming from nuclear power and to reduce
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station in Zhejiang Province, Ling'ao
in Guangdong, and Lianyungang in Jiangsu will have a total
generating capacity of 6.7 million kilowatts, or about half that
of the Three Gorges Project. They will need more than 10 billion
US dollars, he said, and will help raise the proportion of nuclear
power from the current one percent to four or five percent of the
country's total, says Yan Shuheng, secretary-general of the
Chinese Nuclear Society.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power stations require less fuel and produce little
wastes, compared with coal-fired plants, with one
million-kilowatts capacity coal-fired plant consuming about three
million tons of coal each year, and release six million tons of
carbon dioxide, four to five tons of sulfur dioxide, and 300,000
tons of cinder each year.
</P>
<P>
A nuclear power station with similar capacity only needs 30
tons of fuel a year and discharges no carbon dioxide, sulfur
dioxide or other waste gas.
</P>
<P>
China is the biggest coal consumer in the world, using more
than one billion tons year. Estimates are that it produces over 20
million tons of sulfur dioxide each year, and 30 percent of the
country's land has suffered from acid rain.
</P>
<P>
The large amount of carbon dioxide from burning coal can also
affect the environment and international organizations have urged
countries to increase control on carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power stations currently supply 17 percent of the
world's electric power, meaning not discharging 2.3 billion tons
of carbon dioxide from coal each year, they said. Carbon dioxide
emissions would increase by 10 percent if the nuclear power plants
are not used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
