<HEADLINE> Australia Stocks Close Lower As BHP, Rate Hopes Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A fall in resources giant BHP
shares after a lower-than-expected quarterly result and fading
hopes for an interest rate cut combined to drive the Australian
share market lower Friday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 18.4 points to 2,762.7 as the
above factors countered a strong rise in gold stocks on the back
of a firming bullion price.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate-sensitive stocks like banking and retailing
stocks in particular were sold off after comments by Reserve Bank
of Australia Governor Ian Macfarlane implied on Thursday that
rates were on hold for now.
</P>
<P>
"Ian Macfarlane's comments really didn't give us any thought of
a rate cut when the market fairly well expected one, and that was
one of the reasons (the market was down)," Stuart Smith from
Henderson Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason is the options expiry, with most of the volume
going through today, taking money out of the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 5.5 points to 1,183.9 as BHP
slumped 35 cents to 15.65 Australian dollars after reporting a 67
percent fall in third quarter net profit to 83 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The result was below analysts' expectations, and when it was
released it weighed on the market with the resources company
topped turnover with more than 32 million BHP shares exchanged.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto fell six cents to 19.54 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index jumped 35 points, or 3.07 percent, to 1,176.7 as
the bullion price rose 2.35 U.S. dollars per ounce to 301.25
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 34.1 points to 4,740.9, with
telecommunications giant Telstra bucking the trend of the major
stocks to rise another five cents to 3.89 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the major banks, Westpac continued its recent falls with
a 23-cent drop to 10.14 Australian dollars, ANZ was down at 10.35
Australian dollars, National Australia Bank was down 24 cents at
21.74 Australian dollars and Commonwealth closed 25 cents lower at
18.07 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for Friday was 383.9 million shares worth
1.116 billion U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises by 580
to 481. 
</P>
</TEXT>
