<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross in Israel to Begin New Round of Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Deniss Ross arrived here Thursday night to begin another round of
shuttle diplomacy on salvaging the stalled peace process, more
important to sell the U.S. proposal to Israel on troops pullout
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative mainly focus on the Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank, in which the U.S. persuades the
Israeli government to hand over around 13 percent territory to
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) in the next redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Handing over more territories to the PNA remains one of the
biggest unsettled issues hindering the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks. The Israeli government so far has not reached any decision
on the percentage of redeployment, saying that every one percent
territory in the West Bank is critical to Israel security.
</P>
<P>
The current Israeli government has been implementing a hardline
policy in the peace process and the majority within the coalition
oppose handing over any more land to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
In order to save the peace process from total failure, the
U.S. Administration formulated several weeks ago this 13 percent
redeployment proposal and threatened to unveil it without the
endorsement from Israel.
</P>
<P>
This move of the U.S. caught Israel off guard, but the Israeli
government immediately announced its rejection to the proposal,
saying that the U.S. can raise this and that suggestion, but
only Israel can make decisions about its security needs.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Banjamin Netanyahu started his meeting
here Friday morning with Ross to discuss the U.S. proposal, but he
stated on the eve of the meeting that he "can not accept a
diktat," adding that Israel has its own principles.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's communication advisor David Bar-illan also said
Thursday night that it would be utterly impossible for Israel to
withdraw from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Israel may agree to a two-digit pullback
and the exact figure is less than the U.S. proposed, and the areas
to be handed over to the PNA would be "contiguous rather than
scattered pockmarks" among which travel would be difficult and
hazardous for the Israeli settlers.
</P>
<P>
On the redeployment issue, the PNA has adopted a totally
different attitude. PNA chairman Yasser Arafat is reportedly to
demand a three-phased sizable Israeli pullbacks and a freeze in
Israel's settlement activities in the West Bank in his meeting
with Ross scheduled Friday evening in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is also expected to press Ross to divulge details of the
U.S. 13 percent proposal to be carried out over 12 weeks. Arafat
has also hinted that the PNA would only agree to the figure
provided Israel implemented another pullback afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's meeting with Ross was postponed until friday after
a delay in Ross's arrival Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNA also rejected the Israeli suggestion to
offer territorial contiguity, probably to link up the towns of
Jenin and Nablus and perhaps even Ramallah at the north end of
the West Bank and Hebron with surrounding towns in the south.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, viewing the strong rejections from the Israeli side
and the demands from the PNA, it will be hard for Ross to
accomplish his mission and unveil the U.S. initiative during his
current trip to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
