<HEADLINE> US Judge on China's Legal System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nelson said that prisoners should work, and that labor should
not be seen simply as a kind of punishment. It can help inmates
earn a living since they can learn certain working skills through
labor, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the fact that prisoners can work together make jails
in China more like a community, which can help them avoid
psychological problems associated with long-term isolation,
something that is seen quite often in American jails, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
Nelson has had more exchanges with Chinese counterparts in the
1990s and has been following the development of China's legal
system closely and says that has been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
She said she is concerned about China's new Criminal Code, but
that the principle of innocent until proven guilty under the law
in the new code is major progress in China's legal system. This
effectively eliminates the biases of judges in the conviction and
punishment phases, she said.
</P>
<P>
But, China has a lot to do in working toward the goal of "rule
by law", educating the citizens, especially youngsters, better
about the law.
</P>
<P>
There are also flaws in the American legal system, she said,
pointing to the sensational trial of O.J. Simpson that made people
skeptical about the justice in American courts.
</P>
<P>
She concluded the United States and China should understand and
learn from each other in the field of law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
