<HEADLINE> 700 Turkish Rebels Join in Iraqi Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 former members of
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) of Turkey have
surrendered to a major Northern Iraqi party, Western diplomatic
sources said.
</P>
<P>
These former PKK militants are now joining the Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP) forces in the battle against their
former comrades, the Daily News newspaper quoted the sources as
saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
"They are reported to be fighting better than the KDP members,"
they said, failing to tell when and where they crossed over to
the KDP, which is fighting against the PKK and the pro-Iranian
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) troops in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported earlier that Semdin Sakik, former
commander of the PKK forces, had surrendered himself to the
KDP and might be extradited to the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, both Turkey and the pro-Ankara KDP denied the
reports, saying that there is no plan for the extradition of
the former PKK military chief.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government since 1984
for the establishment of an independent Kurdish state in eastern
and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
For Wiping out the outlawed PKK guerrillas operating in
northern Iraq, Turkey has repeatedly launched cross-border
military offensives to strike the PKK camps in northern Iraq,
prompting strong criticism from the international community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Firm Gets Severe Fine for Price-fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- An Australian national trucking
company was fined 2.51 million U.S. dollars Friday for its
"illegal conduct" in asking competitors not to undercut its
freight charges.
</P>
<P>
Justice Peter Heerey, in the Victorian Supreme Court in
Melbourne, imposed the penalty a month after handing down his
decision over the case brought by the Australian Competition and
Consumer Commission (ACCC) against the company of J McPhee and Son
(Australia), the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Four executives of the company were fined between 67,000 U.S.
dollars and 10,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Outside the court, a spokesman for the company said an appeal
to the full bench of the Supreme Court would be lodged against the
judgment and fines.
</P>
<P>
Justice Heerey said that by setting penalties at such a level
the court intended to deter any conduct which is considered "very
damaging" to the Australian community.
</P>
<P>
The judge ruled last month that McPhee had flouted trade
regulations by asking one of its main competitors, Discount
Freight Express (DFE), to "cover" quotes to customers - Just Jeans
and ACI Florapak.
</P>
<P>
The demand was aimed at staving off a threat from rival company
IPEC. This meant that the quotes would not be less than the prices
charged by McPhee.
</P>
<P>
The judge said that members of the McPhee management arranged a
meeting in May 1995 for the purpose of persuading the DFE
Victorian management to put in a cover quote.
</P>
<P>
John McPhee, chairman of McPhee, said in a statement Friday
that "all of us at McPhee Transport are devastated by the court's
judgment and will be strenuously pursuing an appeal to clear the
name of the company and the executives named in the case."
</P>
</TEXT>
