<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Signs Russia's 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed the 1998 federal budget Friday, which has been approved by
the State Duma and the Federal Council (two houses of parliament)
earlier this month, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The budget sets 1998 government spending at 499.9 billion
rubles (about 83.3 billion U.S. dollars) and revenues at 367.5
billion rubles (about 61.2 billion dollars). The maximum budget
deficit may be 132.3 billion rubles (about 22 billion dollars) or
4.7 percent of the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told acting Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, who has
been nominated as premier, to guarantee quarterly report of the
cabinet on the execution of the budget from the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko said Thursday that he would draft the government's
short-term plan of action and a "tentative composition" of the new
cabinet. 
</P>
