<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Zealand Records Worst Balance of Payments Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's balance of
payments deficit in the year to December 1997 hit a record high of
7.5 billion New Zealand dollars (4.2 billion U.S. dollars),
Television New Zealand reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The figure means that New Zealand spent 7.5 billion New Zealand
dollars overseas more than it earned in the year. The deficit
amounted to 7.7 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The deficit occurred at a time when New Zealand experienced a
continuing decline in trade balance as imports were rising faster
than exports.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments deficit is tipped to grow further as
the full impact of the Asian currency crisis is beginning to bite,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The money market responded to the news with a quick rise in
short-term interest rates. The key 90-day bank bills rate climbed
to 9.57 percent Friday, signaling a new round of mortgage rates
hike on the way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
