<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Judge Comments On China's Legal System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A judge of the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, Dorothy Nelson, says she sees many "positive
factors" in China's judiciary after getting a first-hand look at
Chinese courts and prisons.
</P>
<P>
Nelson, who is making her third visit to China, praised the
practise of mediation, education for those who commit minor
crimes, and proper physical labor for prisoners.
</P>
<P>
She told Xinhua that she has been interested in China's legal
system since 1979, when she was appointed to the bench by
President Jimmy Carter and the United States established
diplomatic ties with China.
</P>
<P>
She first came to China in October of 1989, at a time when the
western media were very critical of China. The mediation system
has settled a large number of civil and minor criminal cases
without bringing them to the court. This has not only lightened
the burden on the judges and litigants, but also helped maintain
the harmony of human relationships and social stability, she said.
</P>
<P>
One example she gave was a couple going to court to try to
settle problems in their marriage, where mediation may give them a
new start while a verdict would put an end to the marriage, and
the latter is often the case in the United States, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese judiciary emphasizes education more than punishment
in the case of minor crimes, something that can prevent many
teenagers from going on to commit more serious crimes, she said.
But in the US, minor crimes committed by teens can burden them
with a bad record, something that may have a negative effect for
their entire lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Hold Workshop on Economic Cooperation in C.Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said on Friday that it will continue its series of workshops on
economic cooperation in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said the third workshop, namely the
"Cross-Border Issues and Regional Trade," is schedule to be held
in Urumqi, the People's Republic of China on March 30.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, participants from China, Kazakhstan,
Kirghizstan and Uzbekistan will examine policy-related issues on
regional trade and impediments to cross-border trade, traffic and
travel.
</P>
<P>
Two workshops on economic cooperation in the region were held
in Manila earlier this year to examine the need for infrastructure
investment and policy reform in the energy, trade and payments
systems and transportation and communications.  
