<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Criticizes Greece and Iran for Supporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkish military intelligence has
accused Iran and Greece of supporting Kurdish rebels of Turkey, a
leading Turkish newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The military intelligence sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, were quoted by Daily News as saying that the two
neighboring countries of Turkey have joined hands in providing
support to the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) since
January.
</P>
<P>
The PKK militants were first trained in Greece and then
flown to Iran from where they will infiltrate into Turkey and
northern Iraq, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Three Greek officers are now providing military training,
including the use of heavy artillery, to the PKK members in the
Rzayi camp, which is the second largest one of its kind in Iran,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 11 camps scattered in Iran where the PKK
militants receive military instructions, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been accusing Greece and Iran of rendering financial
and military support to the PKK which has been engaging Ankara for
the Kurdish autonomy in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Iran, which both share bitter relationship with
Turkey, categorically denied the accusations, saying that this
charge is mere propaganda of Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
