<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Brisk Bond Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China's banking system sold state
treasury bonds valued at 98.5 billion yuan between February 20 and
March 24, according to statistics released by the People's Bank of
China, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume represented 82.1 percent of the scheduled
issue of 120 billion yuan in certificate bonds. The total figure
includes 72 billion yuan in three-year bonds and 48 billion yuan
in five-year bonds, according to today's issue of China Securities.
</P>
<P>
The daily reported that the sales volume for the Feb-Mar period
included three-year bonds valued at 62.5 billion yuan and
five-year bonds valued at 35.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that continuing brisk sales will ensure that this
year's bond issue will be completed five to six months of the
scheduled October 31 closing date.
</P>
<P>
Falling interest rates and steadily declining prices have
prompted an increasing number of Chinese citizens to invest in
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
China reduced average interest rates on deposits by 0.16 of a
percentage point on March 25, with the rate for loans falling by
0.6 of a percentage point. The rate cut was the fourth since
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
