<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funding Needed for Temple Refurbishing Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
is seeking financial support for a project to refurbish an ancient
local temple built over 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The project is the largest project of its kind since renovation
of Lhasa's Potala Palace.
</P>
<P>
The two-year project will cost an estimated 32 million yuan,
with the funding coming from the central and regional governments,
as well as from individuals.
</P>
<P>
"Fund-raising activities among people have thus far fallen
short of expectations," according to Zhang Xiusheng, director of
the the project which commenced in last April. He expressed the
hope that businesses and individuals from both at home and abroad
will offer a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
The Longxing Temple, located in Hebei's Zhengding County, was
constructed in the year 971. The temple houses a 21.3 meter high
bronze buddha considered to the largest piece of its kind
fashioned during the period.
</P>
<P>
The building has been refurbished several times, with the last
renovation effort completed in 1944. Experts note that several
small halls were demolished during the last renovation. The
renovation also greatly altered the original appearance of the
temple.
</P>
<P>
Field studies revealed that some structural defects were
seriously endangering the safety of the temple's cultural relics
and bronze buddha. The projected effort aims to restore the
original appearance of the temple. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
