<HEADLINE> SKorea to Launch Special Fund for Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government will
provide a fund of one billion U.S. dollars to the country's
commercial banks for smoothing export without the letters of
credit.
</P>
<P>
The fund will come from loans by the World Bank and other
international institutions, said the Commerce, Industry and Trade
Minister Park Tae-young Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The devaluation of the Korean won against the greenback has
given exporters good opportunities, but actual shipment has not
been as impressive as expected due to the financial and foreign
exchange crisis," said Park.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that his ministry will consider
restoration of the trade financing system, which suspended in 1989
for affiliates of the country's top conglomerates, or chaebols, to
help their export and import business.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the government allocated three billion
dollars to assist businesses import much-needed raw materials amid
fear of troubles of export industries suffering from the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was caused by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans
of financials institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, which is still in the financial crisis, has been
working hard for getting more foreign currency by increasing
export and reducing import since it signed an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund last December for a bailout fund of 57
billion dollars. 
</P>
