<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Cards Becoming More Popular In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A "Gold Card Program" that was
tried out in China's commercial and financial center, Shanghai,
has proven effective in increasing the use of credit cards.
</P>
<P>
The city has set up China's largest urban interbank credit card
network with more than 10 financial institutions like the
Industrial and Commercial Bank, Agriculture Bank, Bank of China,
Investment Bank, Pudong Development Bank, and Shanghai City
Cooperative Bank.
</P>
<P>
The program's slogan "One card means cash in any bank" is
gaining currency in the city as credit cards from each of the
network's banks, as well as post office Green Cards, can be used
at all ATMs and point-of-sales (POS) computer terminals to get
cash, information, or gain access to an account.
</P>
<P>
Since the program's start in 1994, Shanghai has issued over
eight million credit cards and opened 1,700 ATMs and 4,500
POS computer cash registers.
</P>
<P>
More than four million business transactions, worth three
billion yuan, were handled by ATMs last year, a 282 percent
increase from the previous year. POS outlets handled 252,000 deals
in 1997 worth, 158 million yuan, a 541 percent increase from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is making an effort to give greater accessibility to
credit cards by making standards and business procedures closer to
international practices. It got its credit card network connected
to VISA International's ATM network in 206 countries and regions
by last June so that VISA Card owners can get renminbi from
ATMs in Shanghai. By the end of last year, 1.32 million
U.S. dollars worth of business had been done in this way.
</P>
<P>
An "intelligent" credit card is getting more use for paying for
taxi rides, shuttle bus fares, and taxes. Non-banking institutions
have issued over one million such cards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
