<HEADLINE> Drought Reduces Kenya's Tea Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan tea exports fell from
1996's 257 million kilograms to 221 million last year due to
severe drought in the first three months of 1997, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tea exports earned Kenya 366 million U.S. Dollars in foreign
exchange last year compared to 420 million dollars in 1996, a
drop of approximately 14 percent, said the Kenya Tea Growers
Association.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the reduced exports, we expect a bumper harvest this
year as there was continuous rain resulting from the El Nino
weather phenomenon from mid-October last year through to January
this year," said the body in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Besides last year's drought, Kenya's tea industry has also
been hit by constant wrangles between individual tea growers and
the Kenya Tea Development Authority, a management supervisory
body of Kenya farmers. The row culminated in a week-long strike
last month.
</P>
<P>
The strike came at the same time as a total work stoppage in
Sri Lanka's tea industry over wages, which dragged on through
February.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are the world's largest tea producers, with
Sri Lanka producing a record 277 million kgs of tea last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
