<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Supports Certification of Mexico in Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted 54 to 45
Thursday night to uphold President Bill Clinton's endorsement of
Mexico as a reliable ally in the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1961 law, U.S. presidents must certify to Congress
annually that drug-producing countries have "cooperated fully" with
the U.S. on drug-control efforts. Congress then has 30 days to
overturn such a designation.
</P>
<P>
The vote rejected a resolution proposed by senators Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., that would have
overturned Clinton's March certification.
</P>
<P>
In this year's drug control report, Clinton certified Mexico as
being "fully cooperative."
</P>
<P>
However, Feinstein told the Senate that Mexico had cooperated
on the political level with the United States but not at the law
enforcement level.
</P>
<P>
She compared Mexico's drug control efforts to "an inflated
balloon; impressive to look at but hollow at the core and easily
punctured."
</P>
<P>
Opponents said decertification would be counter productive with
a country that shares a long border with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The annual certification process was criticized by countries
that are under investigation. They said this is interference in
their domestic affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India's Vajpayee Govt Likely to Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- India's week-long coalition
government led by Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee is to seek a
vote of confidence in the just-formed 12th lower house of
parliament on Friday or Saturday and it is likely to win the trust
vote, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The trust vote, being sought on the directions of President
Kocheril Raman Narayanan that Vajpayee should prove his majority
in the lower house of parliament in 10 days of his being sworn in,
is scheduled to be discussed and voted Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)-led coalition government was
sworn in on March 19.
</P>
<P>
The BJP Thursday issued a whip to all of its members to be
present in the House on 27 and 28 March and to vote in favor of
the confidence motion which is to be moved by Prime Minister
Vajpayee on Friday. The BJP has also requested all of its allies
to issue a similar whip to their respective members to ensure
victory in the trial of strength.
</P>
<P>
The BJP and its allies held a meeting Thursday evening to
discuss the joint strategy to be adopted by them during discussion
on the confidence motion. They would again be meeting Friday
morning before the commencement of the House sitting to coordinate
cooperation among various constituents of the government.
</P>
<P>
On paper, the government side has a wafer thin majority in a
House with an effective strength of 539 already elected MPs. The
ruling party and its allies have a strength of 264, while the
opposition parties including the Congress and the United Front
have 261 MPs.
</P>
<P>
Top leaders of Telugu Desam Party (TDP), National Conference
and Asom Gana Parishad, who recently parted ways with the United
Front, met on Wednesday and ruled out support to Congress-led
government. The three parties have 14 MPs in the House.
</P>
<P>
TDP sources said its strategy on the confidence motion would be
decided on the floor of the House including a possible last-minute
oral whip in favor of the government.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, opposition parties are bracing themselves up
for a combined onslaught on the multi-party BJP-led government
during the trial of confidence. The Congress has issued a
three-line whip to its members in the House to oppose the motion
of confidence. Other opposition parties are also expected to issue
the similar whips to their members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
