<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Invigilators Warned of Hi-Tech Cheating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Invigilators in Thailand have
been ordered to keep an eye on cheatings using advanced
technologies such as Internet during this year's university
entrance examinations, the Bangkok Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials must be prepared for all kinds of tricks, the
University Affairs Ministry's Anti-cheating Committee warned.
</P>
<P>
Above all, there is the hi-tech cheating device in which
cheating gangs use the Internet to directly transmit answers
through pagers.
</P>
<P>
This method will bypass pager operators and some pagers are as
small as matchboxes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the cheating, invigilators are expected to conduct
a body search on students to find these devices and other
receivers.
</P>
<P>
An anti-cheating committee official predicted that there will
be widespread cheating in this year's university entrance exams in
Thailand since many secondary school students want places at
state-run universities.
</P>
<P>
About 190,000 students have applied for state-run universities
this year, but the universities are able to accommodate only
27,000.
</P>
<P>
Anti-cheating groups have been asked to keep a close watch on
April 5, 8, 9, 11 and 12 when students are tested in difficult
subjects such as English, maths and science.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has sought help from the Post and Telegraph
Department to send mobile radio trucks to scan frequencies used in
the cheating and scramble the signals.
</P>
<P>
Three mobile radio trucks will be placed in Bangkok's
examination venues and six others in the provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
