<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Reform Needed for Thai Economy: UK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand needs further reform to
regain sustainable growth despite its achievement in rebuilding
confidence in the economy, visiting British Economic Secretary to
the Treasury Helen Liddel said.
</P>
<P>
Liddel, who heads a team of British bankers and financiers on a
two-day visit here, held talks with Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai,
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda and other cabinet ministers
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post reported Friday that Liddel suggested Thailand
 undertake an "orderly" privatization of state enterprises, as it
is crucial for economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
While European nations did not want to see a "fire sale" of
assets, Thailand needed to set up credible regulations, reforms
and accounting systems, she said.
</P>
<P>
"This will lead to important efficiency gains in the Thai
economy, as well as significant proceeds which could be used in
recapitalizing the financial sector," she said.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which has undergone significant privatization of state
agencies and utilities over the past decade, was prepared to lend
technical assistance and advice to Thailand, Liddel added.
</P>
<P>
Britain will host the second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
scheduled next week in London. It has proposed establishing an
ASEM trust fund to help provide technical assistance and advice to
Asian countries battered by the regional economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Liddel said Britain is prepared to contribute 5 million pound
(8.3 million U.S. dollars) to the fund, as well as lend technical
assistance to Thailand and other Asian countries to establish
social safety nets and proceed with privatization and structural
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Britain is also expected to lend financial aid to Thailand
through the International Monetary Fund if necessary, she said.
</P>
<P>
A roundtable discussion at the ASEM would focus mainly on the
Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Liddel said European leaders would have a chance to listen to
the problems and learn lessons about the current economic problems
from their Asian counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
