<HEADLINE> Myanmar Holds Military Parade for Armed Forces Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Friday held a grand
military parade, participated by more than 5,000 military men and
members of the Police Force, the Fire Brigade and the Red Cross,
to mark the 53rd anniversary of the Armed Forces Day or Resistance
Day.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, attended by Myanmar leaders, high
officials, military officers and foreign military attaches,
Commander-in-Chief of the Myanmar Defense Services Senior-General
Than Shwe urged the armed forces to endeavor "for emergence of a
peaceful, modern and developed nation and discipline-flourishing
democracy in cooperation with the people."
</P>
<P>
On national reconciliation, Than Shwe, who is also chairman of
the State Peace and Development Council and prime minister, said,
"I would like to state here that our Tatmadaw (defense forces) is
extending the olive branch and keeping the door open for the
remnants."
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1980s, a dozen anti-government ethnic armed
groups have returned to the legal fold and made peace with the
government. However, Kayin National Union (KNU), an
anti-government ethnic armed group on the Myanmar-Thai border,
still has not done so.
</P>
<P>
On foreign policy, Than Shwe stated that Myanmar is adhering to
an independent and active foreign policy based on peaceful
coexistence.
</P>
<P>
"Today, Myanmar stands as an ASEAN member and works for mutual
interest with other ASEAN nations on regional issues and for
national development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Myanmar has also been able to enhance good bilateral relations
and improve friendly ties with all her neighbors," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
