<HEADLINE> Vietnam Signs Agreement With U.S. Investment Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam signed an agreement here on
Thursday allowing the United States Overseas Private Investment
Corporation (OPIC) to operate in Vietnam, the Vietnamese press
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Minister of Planning and Investment, Tran Xuan Gia,
signed for the Vietnamese Government, and U.S ambassador to
Vietnam Douglas P. Peterson witnessed the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement had already been signed by OPIC president George
Munoz in Washington on March 19, following U.S. President Bill
Clinton's March 10 decision to waive the Jackson Vanik Amendment
to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Gia said the signing of the agreement would facilitate OPIC's
activities to support U.S.-funded projects in Vietnam by providing
loans, guarantees to bank loans, insurance and re-insurance for
investment operations.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC will be allowed to provide financial and technical
assistance to U.S. business people to carry out investment
projects in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In a move to implement the agreement, OPIC plans to send a
mission to Vietnam in early April to consider financial assistance
to several U.S.-funded projects.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is a U.S. government agency that supports
long-term direct investments by American businesses in developing
countries. It operates through two principal programs -- a
finance program and an insurance one.
</P>
<P>
The United States has invested 69 projects with a combined
registered capital of 1.232 billion U.S. dollars in Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
