<HEADLINE> Measures Adopted to Protect Baltic Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Baltic Marine Environment
Protection Commission (BMEPC) approved an action strategy and a
series of environment protection proposals at a ministerial
meeting here, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The commission reported that the discharged volume of toxic
wastes into the Baltic Sea dipped by 30 percent in 1995 from 1987,
but failed to meet the BMEPC target of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The commission decided to put off the deadline until the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
The action strategy aims to stop completely the discharge of
hazardous substances to the sea, over the period of a generation.
</P>
<P>
The proposals, which mainly touched on pollution created by
agricultural operations and marine transport, suggest reduced land
cultivation, less fertilizer spreading and the tightening of
animal manure management to decrease the discharged nutritional
substances produced by agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
