<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Train 20,000 Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will launch a major
project to upgrade the teaching of mathematics for primary schools
island-wide at a cost of 490 million rupees (8.1 million U.S.
dollars), the official Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry told the paper Thursday that under the
project 20,000 teachers and 7,500 primary school heads will be
trained within the stipulated period of five years beginning March
this year. They will be given comprehensive training during the
period.
</P>
<P>
Class-based research studies will also be conducted to improve
the standard of the primary mathematics curriculum, text books and
teachers' guide currently in use, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The British Department of International Development and Sri
Lanka's Ministry of Education will fund the project.
</P>
<P>
Under the project it is also proposed to develop a national
plan on primary education to be implemented gradually through a
five-year period beginning from year 2000. 
</P>
