<HEADLINE> Thai PM to Seek Europe's Help at ASEM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
is expected to convince Europe at the Second Asia-Europe Meeting
(ASEM) next month to take concrete measures to restore Thai
economic stability, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Friday quoted the spokesman, Kobsak Chutikul,
as saying Thailand is going to maximize the ASEM summit for the
national agenda of confidence-building.
</P>
<P>
The most urgent task of Chuan's trip to London, the venue of
the ASEM meeting, is to convince European countries to roll over
and restructure corporate debts and provide export credits for
Thai exporters to ensure their cash-flow necessary for operation,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union provided 1.5 billion U.S. dollars of export
credits to Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea in 1997. But this
year soft loans should be increased, Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan will also call on European countries to open their
markets or facilitate market access for Thai products, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recapitalization for Thai financial institutions is another
topic Chuan will cover.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Chuan will explain what steps have been taken
to restore confidence of European investors including a legal
process for the bankruptcy law and alien business law," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will also brief the meeting on the situation
of small and medium enterprises and political and bureaucracy
reforms, he added. 
</P>
