<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Hopes for Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Bulgarian Foreign
Minister Nadezhda Mikhailova said here on Thursday that her
country is willing to work with other countries to help avoid any
fallout from the ethnic tensions in Kosovo, a province of
Yugoslavia's Serbia Republic.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo escalated on March 1 when four Serb
policemen and 16 ethnic Albanian separatists were killed in an
armed conflict, according to earlier reports by the Yugoslavian
news agency Tanjug.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, which borders Yugoslavia, fears the violence between
the Serbian authorities and ethnic Albanians might spread beyond
Kosovo. Neighboring Albania and Macedonia both have large ethnic
Albanian populations.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailova, arriving here for a two-day visit beginning
Thursday from a meeting with the six-nation Contact Group in Bonn,
said further sanctions against Yugoslavia should be made in a
step-by-step manner without inflicting harms to its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, which comprises Russia, Germany, Britain,
the United States, France and Italy, on Wednesday gave Belgrade
four weeks to end the violence in Kosovo, where Albanians
outnumber Serbs by nine to one, or face additional sanctions.
</P>
<P>
During her stay here, Mikhailova discussed the Kosovo crisis
and bilateral trade with her Finnish counterpart Tarja
Halonen. She also met Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and Prime
Minister Paavo Lipponen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
