<HEADLINE> Consortium to Build Argentina-Uruguay Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The gas pipeline that will
eventually connect the Argentine capital of Buenos Aires with
Montevideo, the capital of Uruguay, will be under construction by
October.
</P>
<P>
A consortium formed by a British gas company and an
Argentina-U.S. joint venture won the construction bid Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 215-kilometer Buenos Aires-Montevideo 'gasoduct,' also
called "Gasoducto del Sur," will be completed by the end of 1999
and commence operations on the first day of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
It will initially transport two million cubic meters of natural
gas a day from Argentina to the southern provinces of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The supply will eventually be increased to five million cubic
meters a day, as Uruguayan domestic needs increase.
</P>
<P>
The southern part of Uruguay, with 1.5 million inhabitants,
almost half of the country's total population, is the most
industrial and commercial zone of the country.
</P>
<P>
The gasoduct will promote industrial, agricultural and
livestock development in the region, because it will provide clean
and cheaper energy resources, Uruguayan authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
