<HEADLINE> 60 Sea Tigers Killed in Sri Lankan Air Force Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Air Force attacked
a flotilla of 20 Tamil rebel vessels, killing more than 60 Sea
Tigers (the naval wing of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam)
off the East Coast at Mullaitivu Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Air Force sources, the rebel flotilla is believed
to have been on its way to target a naval base at Trincomalee in
Eastern Province when it was attacked, the Island newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Initially an unmanned aerial vehicle of the Air Force had made
aerial reconnaissance on the flotilla as it set out from its base
at Chalai in the north.
</P>
<P>
This information had helped Air Force pilots to zero in on the
flotilla and four 250-kilogram bombs were dropped on the
unsuspecting Sea Tiger flotilla, taking it by surprise and giving
it no time to beat a retreat when the bombs exploded, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that a loud explosion along with the bombing
indicated that there had been explosives on board the Sea Tiger
ships.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Air Force also claimed that it successfully
bombed a camp in the Paranthan area in Northern Province Thursday
morning, according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
