<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves IMF Spending Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States Senate
approved on Thursday the Clinton administration's emergency
spending request of 18 billion U.S. dollars to finance the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The package, approved unanimously by the Senate, also includes
five billion dollars for disaster relief and military deployments
in the Gulf and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Senate voted 84 to 16 in support of
President Bill Clinton's request for funding the IMF to deal with
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, who has
called the Asian crisis the "El Nino of economics", told the
Senate that failure to deal with the issue promptly would rock
financial markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Dow Jones Industrial Average had been
recently closing on 9,000 points. He stressed: "If we don't act,
the country Had better get ready for a slide on that."
</P>
<P>
The vote, attaching the entire IMF package to an emergency
spending bill for disaster relief and military operations, sets up
an expected confrontation with the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
House Republican leaders have said they want to deal with the
IMF issue separately from the disaster legislation.
</P>
<P>
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., an opponent of the bill, asserted
that IMF austerity programs served to further impoverish
populations and resulted in cheap exports that undercut American
products.
</P>
<P>
"We should use our leverage to change the flawed policies of
the IMF," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., a supporter, argued: ``You can't
remodel the emergency room at the very time patients are being
brought in."
</P>
<P>
The Senate package includes conditions, negotiated between
Republicans and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, urging the
world's major industrial nations to work to reform IMF loaning
practices.
</P>
<P>
The conditions also require countries that receive the IMF
assistance to comply with international trade agreements, and
would urge them to end government-directed lending and subsidies.
</P>
<P>
A House version, not expected to see floor action until after
an April recess, imposes much stricter conditions on the IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, the Senate also adopted a nonbinding
measure by a vote 90-10, calling on the United Nations to
"immediately reduce" the U.S. share of the cost of peacekeeping
operations, from about 30 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
told the Senate that U.S. costs in the Gulf and supporting
peacekeeping operations in Bosnia far surpassed the
U.S. arrearages in United Nations dues. He described it as "money
which we do not owe and should never pay." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinder, AEK Beat Rivals to Reach Final Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Kinder Bologna of Italy and AEK
Athens of Greece reached the Final Four of the European Cup
basketball championship with respective victories in the
quarter-final second leg matches on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
And Turkey's Efes Pilsen tied Italy's Benetton Treviso, CSKA
Moscow tied Partizan Belgrade in other two quarters in the
home-and-away series.
</P>
<P>
Kinder used the last three minutes to score a come-back
victory over city rivals Teamsystem 58-56 and advanced 2-0 on
aggregate into the Final Four in Barcelona, Spain, next month.
</P>
<P>
Guard Hugo Sconochini sunk two free throws in the final minutes
to put his side into the lead for good as Kinder scored six points
en route to overcome 10 points deficit at the halftime.
</P>
<P>
Teamsystem, who lost the first leg 64-52 on Tuesday, put up a
32-11 lead in the earlier time of the match over the slow Kinder,
but saw their advantage cut by Kinder's consitent efforts.
</P>
<P>
American Dominique Wilkins scored the game-hige 23 points on
the night for Teamsystem.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin, the away AEK Athens crushed Alba Berlin's European
Cup Final Four dream as the Greek side won 82-58.
</P>
<P>
Alba, the first-ever German club to reach the last eight of the
competition, trailed at the interval at 40-30.
</P>
<P>
AEK had beaten the German side 88-68 in the Greek capital on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Ankara, Brian Howard's last-minute penalty shot gave Efes
Pilsen a gasping 59-58 victory over Benetton Treviso and sent the
series into the decisive third leg.
</P>
<P>
Efes, who lost in the first leg 67-57 on Tuesday, stormed a
powerful comeback after a 27-24 halftime trailing though they
missed their injured top scorer Petar Naumoski.
</P>
<P>
The third leg will be played in Treviso, Itlay, on April 2.
</P>
<P>
And in Moscow, CSKA Moscow overwhelmed Partizan Belgrade 77-52
to tie 1-1 in series.
</P>
<P>
The hot Partizan, who upset defending champions Olympiakos of
Greece in the last 16, beat the Russians 87-72 at home, and will
have the last game on home court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
