<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Sees Big Trade Surplus in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria saw a trade surplus of 369
million U.S. dollars in its foreign trade last year, the National
Statistical Institute (NSI) announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, trade volume dropped by 1.6 percent from 1996 to 9.8
billion U.S. dollars due to a contraction in imports, the
institute said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe the drastic devaluation of the lev during
the first quarter last year contributed to the import contraction,
which led to a surplus.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary figures, exports of wine and tobacco
dropped by 30 percent and fertilizers by 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
But imports of livestocks and animal products rose by 106
percent.
</P>
<P>
The NSI said that Bulgaria's trade with central and eastern
European countries dropped by 26 percent. Its exports to Russia
fell by 18 percent, to Ukraine by 12 percent and to Macedonia by
34 percent.
</P>
<P>
But exports to Italy and Greece increased by 17 percent, to
Turkey by 15 percent and to the U.S. by 14 percent, the institute
said.
</P>
<P>
Germany, France, Britain, Austria, and the Netherlands were
also among the main trading partners with Bulgaria, which
accounted for 65 percent of Bulgaria's foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
