<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Declines to Reveal Plans for Acting Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has declined to confirm whether acting premier Sergei Kiriyenko
will occupy the post permanently, but brushed aside criticism that
Kiriyenko was too young for the job.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made the remark following Thursday's summit with French
President Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said among the candidates for the post of prime
minister, there is a candidate in his 30s and one turning 70.
</P>
<P>
"That (age) doesn't bother us. The main thing is that the
person has the knowledge and skills a minister needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin appointed 35-year-old Kiriyenko as acting premier on
Monday after firing the entire cabinet headed by former premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
He will name a new prime minister before April. Kiriyenko was
widely viewed as a firm favorite to assume the position.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, the outgoing premier Viktor Chernomyrdin said
in Moscow that his party, Our Home is Russia, will never support
the new government if it attempts to change the route of Russia's
reforms.
</P>
<P>
They will only support a new government which sticks to
reforms, he said after a closed-door meeting of his party.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin has said that he expects to participate in the
formation of the new government.
</P>
<P>
His party discussed at their meeting proposals for new cabinet
members, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
