<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Affects Costa Rica's Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in some
Asian countries will cause a 20 percent decrease in Costa Rica's
exports this year, Ricardo Monge, a Costa Rican economist said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said Costa Rica's textile exports will suffer most from the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Exporters of Costa Rica and other Latin American countries lost
competitivity with the Southeast Asian region because of the
currency devaluation in most countries there, Monge said.
</P>
<P>
But the loss of competitivity was temporary, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Costa Rican producers are considering exporting more
products to the United States, which has absorbed 49 percent of
the exports from the central American country.
</P>
<P>
Also because of the currency devaluations in Southeast Asia,
Monge said foreign investments programmed for there had to be
postponed, and some were probably to be redirected to other
countries. Some would remain in Costa Rica where the government is
strengthening the development of the financial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loan Used To Help Tuberculosis Patients In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- At least 80,000 tuberculosis
patients in central China's Hunan Province have got help through
World Bank loans over the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
There are about 500,000 people who suffer from tuberculosis in
Hunan, and 90,000 new cases each year.
</P>
<P>
In its fight against the disease, the province began using
World Bank loans in 1992 to provide free medicine for the
patients. Since then, 100,000 people have received treatment, and
83,000 have recovered fully, while new incidences have dropped by
more than 10 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, the province has set aside 15 million yuan
in special funds for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
