<HEADLINE> Peruvian Gold Production Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Peru's gold production increased by
17.3 percent in volume and 38.2 percent in value last year,
compared with 1996, the Gold Committee of the Mining and Oil
National Society said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gold production was up from 64.8 tons in 1996 to 76 tons in
1997, and its value rose from 579 million U.S. dollars to 800
million dollars during the same time, Jaime Uranga, the committee
president, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the total gold production was exported and 40
percent was consumed in the local market.
</P>
<P>
Gold bars and concentrates brought in 500 million dollars
while domestic sales earned 300 million dollars, a 20 percent
increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Uranga attributed the increase of domestic sales to higher
activity of the firms that manufacture gold articles, such as
jewelry and chains.
</P>
<P>
The value of gold exports ranked second in the country in 1997,
after copper, said Uranga.
</P>
<P>
Gold mining had created more direct and indirect jobs, and
would continue growing with the development of new projects, he
said.
</P>
<P>
At a world level, Peru achieved the biggest growth in the gold
industry in the past 12 years, Uranga added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
