<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Debt Settlement Plan Awaits IMF Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
come up with a formula to resolve the country's mounting private
debt and would present it to International Monetary Fund (IMF)
officials on Friday, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
The government and the IMF are working on a package of measures
to overcome the country's prolonged economic turmoil, State
Companies Empowerment Minister Tanri Abeng said here Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah has depreciated by over 70 percent
against the U.S. dollar since July last year, making it virtually
impossible for companies to repay their foreign debts which now
total 74 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts held that the private sector foreign debt is
one of the major causes of the monetary crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has been negotiating with foreign
banks and companies for rescheduling the country's private sector
debts.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia Managing Director Miranda Gultom said Thursday
that a suggested six-month postponement of Indonesian companies'
repayments of principal on their debt may not be long enough.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which has suspended its second 3 billion U.S. dollar
disbursement from its 43 billion dollar rescue package to
Indonesia, is now in talks with the country on economic reforms it
agreed upon on January 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
