<HEADLINE> De Bruijn Breaks 50-meter Butterfly Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Inge De Bruijn of the Netherlands
broke the women's 50 meters butterfly European record on the final
day of a two-day World Cup short-course swimming meeting in
Imperia, Italy on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
De Bruijn swam 26.61 seconds, breaking the old record of 26.97
seconds set by German Olympic bronze medallist Sandra Voelker in
Gelsenkirchen, Germany, on February 2, 1997.
</P>
<P>
De Bruijn, who had taken third place in the 50 meters freestyle
and second place in the 100 meters butterfly on Wednesday, held
the European record in the same event for five years between 1991
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch powered home almost one second ahead of compatriot
Angela Postma in 27.58 and Katrin Jaeke of Germany in 27.75.
</P>
<P>
Voelker continued her feat last month in Hong Kong of China,
where she won four gold medals in the FINA World Cup short course
meet, took both the 100 freestyle and 100 backstroke gold medals,
in 54.72 and in one minute 00.23 seconds respectively.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Lorenzo Vismara surprised Olympic champion Alexander
Popov in men's 50 meters freestyle to win the event in 21.97, 0.1
seconds ahead, while Chris Fydler of Australia placed third in
22.42.
</P>
<P>
Fydler, who swam the freestyle leg in Australia's gold-winning
4x100 medley relay at the swimming championships in January, won
the the 200 meters freestyle event in 1.46.29, ahead of Igor
Koleda of Belarus in 1.46.67 and Massimiliano Rosolino of Italy in
1.47.78.
</P>
<P>
The last round of the nine-round World Cup series in 25-meters
pools is to be held in Paris next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
