<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine, Malaysia to Go Into No-Dollar Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
approved the country's entry into a regional currency trading
scheme with Malaysia to reduce dependence on the U.S. dollar,
Manila Standard reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as
saying the scheme will "immediately be implemented" once he signs
in May an agreement with his Malaysian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bilateral agreement involves the netting-out of
trade between the two countries which will be settled in dollars.
</P>
<P>
"You pay only the difference (between exports and imports), so
you reduce the transactions in dollars," Singson said, adding that
the central banks of the two countries would settle their trade
obligations every two months.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, Filipino exporters would have to source pesos
from the central bank, to which importers would be paying also in
pesos. This system will work the same way in Malaysia, Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines and Malaysia would be the first countries in
the Southeast Asian region to enter into the regional currency
trading agreement.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers of the nine-member Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) agreed last month that the trading
scheme should be implemented on a bilateral basis rather than
imposed as a regional mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Philippines and Malaysia, other members of the
ASEAN are Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN has been seeking to reduce dependence on the U.S.
dollar amid a regional currency crisis which triggered the
devaluation of most regional currencies against the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Accept Blatter's Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- World soccer governing body FIFA
said on Thursday that FIFA General Secretary Sepp Blatter would
formally announce his candidature for the presidency of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
A FIFA source said: "The president (Joao Havelange) expects to
be at FIFA House in Zurich tomorrow morning at which time he will
accept a letter from Mr. Blatter which will point out his
candidature for the presidency."
</P>
<P>
Blatter will also step down, temporarily at least, from his
duties as General Secretary while campaigning for the presidency.
FIFA have not yet announced who will take over in his absence,
although it could be his deputy Michel Zen-Rufinen.
</P>
<P>
Joao Havelange, who is stepping down as FIFA president in June
after 24 years ruling, has been actively canvassing for Blatter
for many months and endorsed him again in Zurich recently.
</P>
<P>
"If he decides to stand, I will be delighted because he will
make a first class president," said Havelange.
</P>
<P>
"Many General Secretaries have followed their presidents into
the role and why should there be any difference in this case."
</P>
<P>
It is understood that at least three national associations have
indicated they are prepared to formally nominate Blatter by the
time nominations close on April 7, although a spokesman for the
Trinidad and Tobago association denied on Thursday they had
already done so.
</P>
<P>
"We have made no public decision on Mr. Blatter's candidature
yet," said a spokesman, "because as far as we are concerned he has
not yet declared his interest."
</P>
<P>
UEFA President Lennart Johansson of Sweden is the only declared
candidate at present.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for bids to succeed Havelange is April 7 and the
election will take place at the FIFA Congress in Paris on June 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
