<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis to Dominate ASEM II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in Asia will
be the dominant issue at the Second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM II)
next week in London, a British diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
ASEM II is expected to result in an initiative increasing
European technical assistance to the troubled economies, British
Ambassador to Indonesia Robin Christopher said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The initiative will focus on the financial sector restructure
and poverty impact assessment," Antara News Agency Friday quoted
Christopher as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said Britain has proposed the establishment of an ASEM
trust fund at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"The trust fund is aimed at assessing the poverty impact of the
crisis by looking at the implications for public expenditure
priorities, social action programs and enterprise development to
generate employment opportunities," he noted.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide assistance for financial sector
restructuring, including bank monitoring and supervision,
corporate governance and accounting standards, he added.
</P>
<P>
Christopher disclosed that Britain will provide 50 million
pounds sterling in credit re-insurance for private sector credit
agencies which have stopped covering for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The British envoy said he believes Asia, including Indonesia,
will recover from the crisis and the remarkable record of economic
growth in the region will resume.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe that the roaring tigers of 1997 have turned
into tame pussy-cats overnight. They will surely resume their real
nature," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Asian crisis, ASEM II will discuss three other
important points identified at the first meeting in Bangkok,
namely to foster political dialogue, reinforce economic
cooperation and promote cooperation in other areas.
</P>
<P>
"ASEM II is likely to produce a number of new initiatives,
covering trade, investment, environment -- both management and
disaster preparedness," Christopher said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
