<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Referees Forecast No Red Card Bonanza in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- World soccer governing body FIFA
and their World Cup referees estimated that there would be no red
card bonanza over the tackle from behind during the World Cup
finals this summer.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Thursday, the referees said they
were happy with the definition of the tackle from behind that
comes into effect in the finals starting in France on June 10.
</P>
<P>
"I really don't think referees are going to go crazy and use a
lot of red cards," David Will, president of the world body's
referees committee said.
</P>
<P>
"We're not adding many to the tackles already deserving red
cards," he told a news conference at the end of the World Cup
referees' workshop outside Paris this week.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to see players taken out of the game like
(Marco) van Basten, for instance, with this kind of tackling,"
Will said.
</P>
<P>
Argentine referee Javier Castrilli, known as 'Lawman' in South
America because of his strictness, said: "FIFA are putting the
accent on fair play. This (ruling) is eloquent proof of that.
</P>
<P>
"From the World Cup all players who attack (another) from
behind with a tackle including a follow through will get a red
card," he said when pressed to describe the action that will be
punished by a sending off.
</P>
<P>
But Italian Pierluigi Collina said: "It depends on the approach
of the defender. The most important thing is that the integrity
of the player (being marked) is preserved.
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't matter if you touch the ball or not. You can't
anticipate what the player (with the ball) is going to do, but he
has to be free (to play the ball)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Collina said there would be no more pressure on referees than
when they had to first apply the so-called professional foul
ruling, bringing down a player with a scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
Will said that there were basically two scenarios for the
tackle from behind that FIFA had been through with the referees
during their seminars from Tuesday to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The first has a player with the ball at his feet, perhaps
still, perhaps moving, perhaps preparing to part with it. A player
comes from behind and removes the (other) player, who doesn't even
see his opponent coming, from the game.
</P>
<P>
"There is almost certainly an injury in such circumstances and
this should always have been punished with a red card, that's
nothing new," Will said.
</P>
<P>
"What is new is if a player is off and running with the ball
and an opponent comes from behind and clips his feet from under
him. It's perhaps not particularly violent but deliberately takes
the player from the game.
</P>
<P>
"It's what in English we call the professional foul. The
difference is that now no matter where (it occurs) on the field of
play it gets a red card. Before it was only in a goal scoring
situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that whereas before referees weighed up whether to
punish such a tackle with a yellow or red card, they could no
longer opt for anything other than sending the culprit off.
</P>
<P>
"We have removed the doubt in referees' minds. Players must not
be permitted to attack (another) player."
</P>
<P>
Asked how referees would deal with the situation if a player
feigned being injured when challenged from behind, Will said
feigning in general was covered in a seminar.
</P>
<P>
"This is the worst kind of cheating and referees were made
aware of this not just for the tackle from behind," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It won't be easy," Will admitted. "But it is FIFA's
determination to end deliberate taking out of a player."
</P>
<P>
Will said FIFA were producing a video with examples of the kind
of tackle they are trying to stamp out to show referees and the 32
teams that will play in the June 10-July 12 tournament "and
perhaps even to the media". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0246 </DOCNO>
