<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Foreign currency deposits in Argentina grew 1.9
percent in February and loans to the private sector 1.4 percent
over the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency deposits increased 4.2 percent in current
accounts, and 2.2 percent in fixed terms above January, said
Argentina's Banks Association.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Motor vehicle sales will drop from 35 percent to 40
percent in Venezuela in 1999, forecast Jose Luis Hernandez,
president of the Chamber of Venezuelan Manufacturers of Motor
Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The source attributes the drop to the fact that 1999 is a
post-electoral year, the overvaluation of the currency could be
reduced and the possible rise of interest rates in the first
months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican exports will reach 10 billion
U.S. dollars in the year 2000, forecast the Foreign Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Sales abroad of this Central American country will reach 15
billion dollars by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican exports in 1997 reached 4.813 billion dollars, a
10.75 percent increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil registered a 747 million dollar trade
deficit in the first two months of the year, said the Ministry of
Industry, Commerce, and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
The deficit resulted from imports for 8,376 million dollars,
which surpassed exports for 7,629 million dollars during the
period.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased 11.7 percent and imports contracted 0.61
percent, compared to the same period of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
