<HEADLINE> New Rules to Be Enforced in Auckland Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 27 (Xinhua) -- New strict rules are expected
to go into force on Friday in the prison in New Zealand's largest
city Auckland where inmates staged a riot on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new rules include locking prisoners in their cells for
longer time a day and cutting the weekly visits to just one for
some inmates, the Wellington newspaper The Dominion reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inquiries are being conducted by the police, the
fire service and the correction department into the riot.
</P>
<P>
The riot, involving 48 inmates at the peak, was put down
Thursday night with all the prisoners herded back to their cells.
Twelve defiant prisoners were removed from the jail and sent to
another one.
</P>
<P>
The rioters had set fires on the prison, badly damaging some
cells. But no one was injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
