<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Gov't Unveils Radical Welfare Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- British Social Security Minister
Frank Field unveiled plans Thursday to overhaul the old welfare
system by turning the country from a welfare state to a "self-help
state."
</P>
<P>
By publishing a "green paper" consultative document, Field
promised a host of new welfare policies, built on the principle of
work for all those who were capable, already a prominent feature
of many of its policies.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament that the current system promoted fraud and
deception and had led to poverty and dependence, and the
government sought to replace the cycle of dependency and
insecurity with ethics of work and savings.
</P>
<P>
"Work is the best form of welfare. To those of working age we
offer greater help to get into work, and a modern system to
provide help for those in genuine need who can't work," Field
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the basic state pension remained guaranteed,
he was considering plans to make second pensions compulsory.
</P>
<P>
The paper, which took the Labor government 10 months to draw
up, set out a list of eight principles that will underpin the
reform, along with a list of benchmarks against which progress can
be judged.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair has made welfare reform a central
plank of his government's program since he formed the cabinet in
May last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Help Asia Fight Environment Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Thursday announced an EU initiative to help Southeast Asian
countries better prepared to deal with natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, to be managed by the European Community
Humanitarian Office (ECHO), aims to transfer the technology,
skills and management needed to combat fires, floods, earthquakes,
typhoons and pollution from toxic substances.
</P>
<P>
The ECHO program, which will include Malaysia, Vietnam,
Indonesia, the Philippines and Thailand, also envisages training
farmers in land use techniques and forest management to limit soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
"It is an example of practical diplomacy and partnership at
work and one that will make a real difference to the lives of
people in the region," Robin Cook told a news conference to launch
the scheme.
</P>
<P>
The ECHO has already earmarked 1 million pounds (1.7 million
U.S. dollars) for the initiative and is planning for substantially
more funds available in future years.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, already approved in preparatory meetings, will
be endorsed by Asian and European leaders when they meet in London
next week for the second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM 2).
</P>
<P>
Environment will be an important issue in ASEM 2, which will
draw heads of government from 25 Asian and European nations, Robin
Cook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Shows Gestures to Iran for Improvement of Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Indications show that the
Clinton administration is making some small gestures toward Iran
and has eased off its customary anti-Tehran rhetoric as part of an
effort to improve relations.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin confirmed Thursday at a
regular briefing that the administration had given permission to
Mohammad Hadi Nejad-Hosseinian, Iran's top diplomat at the United
Nations, to travel to Los Angeles and deliver a speech on April 2
at an Iran-U.S. symposium sponsored by the World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
"We have given permission for the Iranian U.N. permanent
representative to travel outside New York City to deliver a speech
to a private American group in Los Angeles," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said such an overture was quite rare as Iranian
officials at the United Nations could only travel within a limited
area of New York City.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said the administration had granted a visa to the
director of women's affairs of Iran so that she could deliver a
speech in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said Rubin's comments on the state of U.S.-Iranian
relations were notably devoid of the traditional emphasis on the
areas of disagreement such as U.S. allegations of Iranian support
for terrorism, development of weapons of mass destruction and
efforts to undermine the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States was encouraged for the warmth and
courtesy Iranians had shown to American visitors lately.
</P>
<P>
Recently, six American scholars, including two former U.S.
government officials, attended a conference on Gulf security in
Tehran as guests of the Iranian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't have one word of hostility aimed at me. No one was
trampling on any (U.S.) flags," said Roscoe Suddarth, a former
State Department official who was among the six-scholar group.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States hoped to have direct talks with
the Iranian government. But since Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said it would be premature to hold
government-to-government talks, the United States would pursuing
people-to-people contacts.
</P>
<P>
"we have said that we are facilitating people-to-people
exchanges by working with private American organizations who wish
to host Iranian visitors or send groups to Iran," Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980327.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainstorm Hits Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains, gale-force winds
and snowfalls have been sweeping most parts of Greece since
Wednesday, causing extensive flooding, power shortage and
black-outs, traffic snarls and flight cancellations.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government held an emergency meeting later Thursday
to discuss measures to deal with the problems caused by the bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
Schools have been ordered to be closed Thursday as both
domestic and international flights were canceled at the Athens
airport.
</P>
<P>
Domestic flights were being diverted to the northern Kavala's
Alexander the Great airport while Thessaloniki's Macedonia airport
was receiving international flights.
</P>
<P>
The bad weather has affected the power stations in the country
with black-outs being reported throughout Greece, bringing trolley
buses to a standstill in Athens for more than two hours and
causing problems to the city's rail network.
</P>
<P>
In Athens' southern suburb of Glyfada, some 5,000 trees are
estimated to have been uprooted by gale-force winds and 75 cars
were damaged by falling trees. Floodings have caused extensive
damage to 20 homes and 45 stores in the area.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of villages in the western Peloponnese peninsula and
northern Greece have been cut off by heavy snowfalls.
</P>
<P>
In the southeastern island of Rhodes, one man died while trying
to moor his boat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
