<HEADLINE> Pentagon Insists on F-22 Fighter Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon Thursday rejected
a congressional agency suggestion that the program for developing
F-22 fighters should be delayed because of engineering problems
and a lack of testing.
</P>
<P>
The F-22 is designed to replace aging F-15s and F-16s in the
coming century, U.S. Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon
said at a Pentagon news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The plane, using stealth or radar-evading technology and is
intended primarily to combat enemy fighter aircraft, is the
premier Air Force weapons program.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to make the program work," said Bacon. "We want to
stay on schedule."
</P>
<P>
The Air Force says that a delay of the program recommended by
the General Accounting Office (GAO) would add billions of dollars
into the most recent estimate of 62 billion U.S. dollars. That is
187 million dollars per plane.
</P>
<P>
The GAO said in a report disclosed by U.S. media that the
Pentagon should delay a decision to spend 595 million dollars on
the first two production planes until late 1999. But the Air Force
insisted it was ready to approve production in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
"A 12-month slip is not something we're contemplating," Bacon
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
