<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanon's Anti-Sectarianism Effort Meets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi's
crusade against the sectarian political system did not have a
smooth start as his proposal of civil marriage designed for the
purpose has met strong opposition.
</P>
<P>
Under his proposal, civil issues as marriage and divorce will
be authorized by government institutions rather than religious
courts.
</P>
<P>
It is intended to pave the way for the marriage between
Lebanese with different religious belief and who refuse to convert.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi has aimed his proposal, if approved by the Parliament to
become law, at helping the Lebanese get together by ending the
sectarian political and social system, which has led to three
civil wars since 1860.
</P>
<P>
"My goal is to eliminate all forms of sectarianism ..., the
country has had enough sectarianism," Hrawi said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief in "absolute equality among the
Lebanese," saying that "we must achieve this so as to get rid of
the rule of sects."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has 17 different religious sects, which control the
country's political and social life.
</P>
<P>
He contended that the president, the parliament speaker and the
prime minister should work for the entire nation, not for separate
sects.
</P>
<P>
Under the Lebanese constitution, the country's president comes
from the Maronite catholic, the prime minister from the Sunni
Muslims and the parliament speaker from the Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
As many have expected, Hrawi's proposal has brought about deep
rifts among different political and religious groups and is
causing hot debate.
</P>
<P>
The country's Islamic clerics have branded the proposal of
civil marriage as "a violation of the core of Islamic religious
thought and belief."
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the cabinet approved the bill on March 18, Sheikh
Mohammed Madhi Shamseddine, spiritual leader of the Shiite
Muslims, and Sheikh Mohammed Rasheed Kabbani, the mufti of the
Sunni Muslims, issued a joint statement condemning the proposal as
an "insult" to the Muslims and therefore it is "illegitimate."
</P>
<P>
They vowed they will spearhead a national campaign to confront
the "dangerous proposal," which they said they will never accept
under any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Around the country, Muslims who oppose the proposal stage
protests after Friday prayers, attacking politicians for pushing
ahead with the bill.
</P>
<P>
Patriarch Nasrallah Butros Sfeir, spiritual leader of the
Maronite community, Lebanon's largest Christian sect, has expressed
his opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
Civil marriage will go against the church's teachings, he said,
warning that the couples who engage in civil marriage will be
shouted out of the church.
</P>
<P>
Despite opposition from religious sects, the country's
politicians and intellectuals, including 21 ministers of the
30-member cabinet and Parliament Speaker Nabih berry, have
expressed their support for Hrawi's proposal.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and five of his followers in
the cabinet voted against the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said he did not oppose the civil marriage itself, but
the timing of the proposal when "Lebanon and the region as a whole
are passing a critical phase and require a high degree of unity
and vigilance."
</P>
<P>
"We must avoid any issue that could have a negative impact on
national unity or lead to divisions inside or outside the
cabinet," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Hrawi has said the prime minister must comply with the
cabinet decision, or has to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
