<HEADLINE> Former French PM Reserved Over Idea of Banning FN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Former French Prime Minister
Raymond Barre Thursday expressed his reservation over the idea of
banning the far-right National Front (FN), because he said it is
"a party which respects the rules of public order."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Figaro to be published
Friday, Barre said that a banning of the FN could result in "a
flow of votes to the extreme left," which has risen over the past
10 months since the Socialist-led leftwing coalition came to
power.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of discontent of the voters who supported the
leftwing coalition in the last legislative elections, the French
Troskyist extreme-left groups, such as Lutte Ouvriere, won 4 plus
percent of votes in the regional elections held on March 15 and
entered the regional parliament in Paris for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Barre, who is now mayor of the central industrial city of Lyon
elected from the center-right Union for French Democracy (UDF),
also suggested that all political leaders of the Gaullist Rally
for the Republic (RPR) and the UDF reach a gentlemen's agreement
to avoid an alliance between the FN and rightwing politicians in
future elections.
</P>
<P>
He also said that one should not ally with the FN under
whatever excuses. He expressed his dismay over the acceptance of
FN votes by former Defense Minister Charles Millon when seeking
reelection to regional council presidency in Rhone-Alpes region,
in which Lyon is located. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
