<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Proposes New Rules on Transplant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government said
Thursday that there should be regulations for organ transplant so
that those who need them most can get them first.
</P>
<P>
Health and Human Services (HHS) Secretary Donna Shalala said
the new plan would be fairer and would save lives.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 54,500 people on the national transplant
waiting list, and 10 people die every day while waiting for an
organ transplant.
</P>
<P>
"The point is to make sure you are treated fairly and equitably
no matter where you are in the country," Shalala told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"My concern and the reason for this regulation is that people
are dying unnecessarily, not because they don't have health
insurance and not because they don't have adequate care, but
simply because of where they live in this country," she said.
</P>
<P>
Under her proposal, the essentially regional system for organ
allocation should be replaced by a single national list.
</P>
<P>
Under the current system, a donated organ is first made
available locally, and if there is no one who needs it or whose
tissue matches it, it is offered regionally and then nationally.
</P>
<P>
Shalala said that under the current system, sometimes people
with less need got an organ before someone with a greater need.
</P>
<P>
"The system was so decentralized that the movement and
allocation of organs have not followed need," Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
She said it should be changed "so that an accident of location
doesn't affect whether you live or die." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
